<HEADLINE> Six Killed in Two Small Plane Crashes in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Two small planes crashed
in South Carolina and California respectively Sunday, killing all
six people aboard, said reports reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
A twin-engine Piper Aerostar crashed near Myrtle Beach, South
Carolina, Sunday afternoon in an emergency landing. But the pilot
managed to avoid restaurants, homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
All the four people aboard the plane were killed and a man who
was walking his dog was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
The plane was heading to York, Pennsylvania, where the four
victims lived.
</P>
<P>
Engine trouble was found after it had taken off from Grand
Strand Airport and the pilot called in a distress signal and tried
to turn around to go back to the airport.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, another twin-engine plane crashed in northern
Los Angeles County, California, killing both people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The Cessna 310 went down in a residential neighborhood of Santa
Clarita, about 50 kilometers northwest of downtown Los Angeles. No
one on the ground was hurt and no homes were damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
