<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Calls for Action on Financial Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign
Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia said Monday that an inactive
attitude toward the impact of the Asian financial crisis can have
a high cost.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the U.N. General Assembly, he said the measures
adopted by world economic powers to tackle the impact of the
crisis "still fall short of what is needed."
</P>
<P>
"The events of the past few months have revealed a serious lag
between growing financial interdependence and the modest
effectiveness of existing international mechanisms for dialogue
and coordination," Lampreia said.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia, the first speaker at the general debate of the 53rd
session of the General Assembly, said the world cannot depend only
on the willingness, capacity and interest of a select number of
countries to mobilize and lead international efforts to deal with
global economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil will continue to fight for a more balanced allocation
of the benefits of economic interdependence, without distortions
such as those resulting from protectionist policies of developed
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the current context of global economic turbulence, we must
demand from the developed nations greater coherence between
free-trade rhetoric and their unfair trade practices," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
