<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Statistics on Africa Depressing, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni said that the AIDS statistics on Africa are extremely
depressing when opening an international conference
on AIDS here Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said over two thirds (or 21 million men, women and
children) of people living with AIDS around the world are in
sub-Sahara Africa. The cumulative number of AIDS orphans in the
continent was 7.8 million at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Sahara African countries account for 83 percent of AIDS
deaths in the world, 87 percent of the children living with AIDS
and 80 percent of women suffering the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The president also said that unprotected sex accounted for
most of the 3.4 million new HIV infections among adults in
sub-Sahara Africa in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of a cure, emphasis should be placed on safe
sexual behavior and increased health education to reduce the
menace of the virus. He called for observance of protected sex
and no pre-marital sex.
</P>
<P>
The top killer in Africa can be overcome in the long run if
the political will exists to make it happen, he added.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been awarded a World Health Organization award for
its remarkable achievements made in checking the spread of
HIV/AIDS. The infection rate in rural areas has dropped from over
30 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Now some estimates say one tenth of Uganda's 20 million
population are HIV-positive and some 500,000 people have died of
AIDS since the first case was reported in the country in 1982.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
