<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Expects Tripartite Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian permanent envoy to
the Arab League Mohammed Sobeih said on Monday that the U.S. is
preparing for a tripartite summit on the Mideast peace process
among leaders of the U.S., Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, among U.S. President Bill Clinton, PNA President
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the
fringe of the 53rd U.N. General Assembly session, will be part of
the U.S. efforts, under the U.N. sponsorship, to push forward the
Israeli-Palestinian preace process, Sobeih told Egypt's Middle
East News Agency (MENA).
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official expressed the hope that the proposed
summit would lead to positive concrete results.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the recent tour of the U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross to the region failed to achieve any headway and
that the pessimism is still prevailing the Palestinian circles.
</P>
<P>
Ross' 12th mission to the Middle East failed to lead to a
breakthrough in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process stalled
since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has put forward a proposal calling for a 13.1 percent
Israeli withdrawal in the next stage of troop redeployment in the
West Bank. The PNA has accepted, but Israel has not.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative is very clear and indivisible whole, Sobeih
said, pointing out that the Palestinian side accepts it provided
no changes could be introduced to it by the U.S. or Israel.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the plan does not meet the provisions of the
U.N. resolutions and the signed agreements, said Sobeih.
</P>
<P>
Israel is demanding that 3 percent of the proposed land be
turned into nature reserve where Israel retains full security
control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sobeih said that Arafat will underscore in his
address to the U.N. General Assembly session a number of questions
concerning the destabilized situation in the region due to the
Israeli uncompromising policies.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly session will serve as an opportunity for
addressing the international community and urging it to bring
pressures on Israel, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
