<HEADLINE> Nine Men Arrested in Connection With Omagh Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Nine men were arrested in
connection with the Omagh bombing early Monday morning, police on
both sides of the Irish border said.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said six people had been arrested in the
province, and the rest three were detained in connection with the
theft of a maroon-colored car used for the bomb attack on 15
August in which 29 people were killed and more than 200 injured.
</P>
<P>
The arrests were carried out by the police force of both sides
of the border at about 5 am Monday and the suspects were flown to
barracks in Armagh, where questioning was taking place, according
to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
An Irish police spokesman said the men they detained were being
questioned about the theft of the car used in the bombing. It was
stolen in Carrickmacross, Co Monaghan, a few days before the
attack.
</P>
<P>
"A number of arrests have been made in connection with serious
crime in the Tyrone area," a Northern Irish spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The "Real IRA," a dissident group of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), claimed responsibility for the bomb which exploded in the
town's main street. But it called a "complete cessation" of
violence two weeks ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
