<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Economic Crisis Calls for Global Solution: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Asian downturn has
triggered a worldwide economic crisis and all parts of the
international system need to come together to find global
solutions to this truly global crisis, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Annan was delivering a speech at the
opening of the two-week general debate of the 53rd session of the
General Assembly. Speakers from 181 countries, including 26 heads
of state and 19 prime ministers, are expected to take the floor to
voice their views on a wide range of matters of international
concern.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian downturn has triggered a worldwide economic crisis,
with devastating social consequences," he said. "Some of the most
successful economies have been plunged into recession, at a speed
which has taken the whole international community by surprise."
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, which broke out in July 1997 in
Thailand, has spread to Russia, and even the markets of North
America and Europe are not immune.
</P>
<P>
"As usual, it is the most vulnerable groups which are the
hardest hit," Annan said. "The countries whose economies had taken
only the first faltering steps on the road of recovery are the
ones that now find themselves in greatest jeopardy."
</P>
<P>
The solution to the current economic turmoil worldwide lies in
the global efforts, rather than the talks by the Group of Seven
industrialized countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to get together to find the answers, but who should
sit at the table? The day is past when the seven major
industrialized powers could or should take on the task alone," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Nor can this crisis be left only to finance ministers and
central bankers, although their contribution is essential," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"All parts of the international system need to come together,
to find global solutions to this truly global crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
For the issues this crisis raises are not just financial or
economic -- or social or political for that matter: they are all
of those things at once, he said, adding that "they must be
addressed on all those fronts."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, which is the global institution par
excellence, has "an inescapable duty to respond," he said, voicing
his hope to see the U.N. participation in discussions on the new
world "financial architecture," such as those suggested by U.S.
President Bill Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Global Action Against Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday called for global action in an anti-terrorism
campaign because individual action by U.N. member states cannot
provide a solution.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism is a global menace, which clearly calls for global
action," he said. "Individual actions by member states, whether
aimed at state of non-state actor, cannot in themselves provide a
solution. We must meet this threat together."
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-week general debate of the 53rd session of the
General Assembly, Annan said that a dramatic increase in attacks
on U.N. and associated personnel "prompts us to reflect on the
conditions in which we send civilian staff into war zones where,
too often, combatants seem less and less willing to respect their
neutral status."
</P>
<P>
Annan condemned networks of terrorism and drug trafficking and
the August 7 bombings in Kenya and Tanzania that killed hundreds
of Africans in assaults on two American embassies. Washington took
a unilateral step to retaliate with missile attacks on alleged
terrorist sites in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We had perhaps the most frightening glimpse yet of this
uncivil society a few weeks ago, with the terrorist bombings in
Nairobi and Dar es Salaam," he said. "What shocks us about
terrorism is its indiscriminate character. Unhappily we have also
to be concerned about violence that is more precisely targeted."
</P>
<P>
"I regret to say, also, that the perpetrators of these attacks
are almost never brought to justice," Annan added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Calls for Action on Financial Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Foreign
Minister Luiz Felipe Lampreia said Monday that an inactive
attitude toward the impact of the Asian financial crisis can have
a high cost.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the U.N. General Assembly, he said the measures
adopted by world economic powers to tackle the impact of the
crisis "still fall short of what is needed."
</P>
<P>
"The events of the past few months have revealed a serious lag
between growing financial interdependence and the modest
effectiveness of existing international mechanisms for dialogue
and coordination," Lampreia said.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia, the first speaker at the general debate of the 53rd
session of the General Assembly, said the world cannot depend only
on the willingness, capacity and interest of a select number of
countries to mobilize and lead international efforts to deal with
global economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"Brazil will continue to fight for a more balanced allocation
of the benefits of economic interdependence, without distortions
such as those resulting from protectionist policies of developed
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the current context of global economic turbulence, we must
demand from the developed nations greater coherence between
free-trade rhetoric and their unfair trade practices," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
