<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zyuganov Calls for Peaceful Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Communist Party
leader Gennady Zyuganov Monday called for a peaceful protest
against wage arrears all over the country scheduled for October 7,
the Interfax news agency reported from Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
The communist leader said that it would not be in the interests
of Russia's left-wing groups if confusion were to break out during
a nationwide protest campaign.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov is attending a Council of Europe Parliamentary
Assembly session which opened in Strasbourg Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov told reporters that the Communist party leadership had
advised campaign organizers to pay special attention to safety
precautions and make close contact with the Interior Ministry and
other law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if participants of the campaign are not
provoked, everything will be fine. "It will be a well-organized
and mass-scale protest action," Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he denied that demands for dismissing the government
would be made during the protest campaign.
</P>
<P>
On the current situation in Russia, Zyuganov said that he is
satisfied that crisis had been avoided and an experienced person,
who is well known in Europe and can conduct dialogue with
different forces, came to head the government.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow Times cited Andrei Issayev, secretary of the Russian
Federation of Trade Unions, as reporting earlier that up to 36
million people will take to the streets all over Russia on October
7.
</P>
<P>
The union estimated that total wage arrears are more than 76
billion rubles. That would have equaled more than 12 billion U.S.
dollars at the rate of 6.2 rubles to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
