<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan President Meets U.S. Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to Angola,
Danald Steinberg, at a meeting with Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos Monday, said that the U.S. has decided to invest 350
million U.S. Dollars in the Angolan petroleum sector.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Steinberg conveyed to the Angolan president a
letter from U.S. President Bill Clinton. But the ambassador,
declining to disclose the contents of the letter, only said that
he and President Dos Santos had exchanged views on the Angolan
peace process and the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has decided to offer Angola new
assistance, investing 350 million Dollars into Angola's petroleum
sector, said Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government will increase its assistance in
such fields as the removal of land mines and the restoration of
agriculture in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president and the U.S. ambassador also held talks
about other issues concerning trade and economy, including the
possibility of a new loan agreement between the Angolan
government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Referring to the situation in Angola, Steinberg said that "the
peace process has fallen into a difficult stalemate."
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the U.S. Embassy here last Friday
called on the Angolan government and the opposition National
Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to hold dialog
within the framework of the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol in a bid
to ward off a war.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the U.S. government condemned the UNITA for
its delay in the process and had voted for the resolution
recently passed by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. said that the series of measures taken by
the Angolan government "may backfire."
</P>
<P>
In order to break the ice, the Angolan government took some
major steps since early September. It first suspended some UNITA
members as ministers or deputy ministers in the government of the
national unity and as the members of parliament in the People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Angolan government acknowledged the breakaway UNITA
Renovation Committee as the only dialogist in the peace talks and
asked the international community to accept its status.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government declared that it stopped any contact
with UNITA President Jonas Savimbi, denouncing him as "the chief
war criminal."
</P>
<P>
President Dos Santos and the U.S. Ambassador also discussed
the latest developments in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
and ways to restore peace and stability in that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
