<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Backs Peaceful Solution to Cyprus Problem: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Czech official said
Monday that Prague supported a peaceful solution to the Cyprus
problem based on a U.N. bi-communal federation formula.
</P>
<P>
Michael Zantovsky, head of a Czech Senate delegation which is
on a four-day visit to Cyprus, made the remarks after his meeting
with Cypriot House Speaker and acting President Spyros Kyprianou and
acting Foreign Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou.
</P>
<P>
Zantovsky told reporters that the Czech Republic "does not
recognize the use of force in international relations and illegal
occupation of territory."
</P>
<P>
"In the past, we had our own sad experience with such matters,
so we are just like Cyprus a small country and we do feel
solidarity with other small nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway republic
in 1983, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify the
Mediterranean island through a bi-communal federation formula.
</P>
<P>
Zantovsky noted that it is in the interest of the two countries
to exchange information and to help each other in the course of
the European Union (EU) accession.
</P>
<P>
The EU began accession talks with Cyprus in March and removed
Turkey from its immediate membership list, which have courted
protest from Turkish Cypriots and deadlocked the peace talks as a
result.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kyprianou said that "we will try our best to see
that the close cooperation between the two countries becomes even
closer."
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou stressed that "the Czech Republic was and
remains by the side of Cyprus and it is one of the countries on
which we lay our hopes in efforts for EU accession and just
resolution of the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
During its stay in Cyprus, the seven-member Czech delegation
will discuss with other government officials on the two countries'
EU accession course and recent developments in Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 45,000 Ethiopians Die of TB Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- About 45,000 people die
of Tuberculosis (TB) annually in Ethiopia and the disease has
become the number one killer in the country, a senior TB expert
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an annual review meeting of the National TB and
Leprosy Control Program, Takele Geressu said there are 90,000 new
detected TB cases in the country and the prevalence of TB is
estimated now to be ranging between 90,000 and 100,000 throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted Takele as saying that as TB
kills the fittest, the disease mostly attacks people at their
most productive age, between 15 and 49.
</P>
<P>
According to the expert, a Directly-Observed Treatment Short
Course (DOTS) has been launched in seven regions of the country
in order to prevent and control the TB epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Although the program has planned to curb 80-85 percent of TB
patients in the regions where DOTS was launched, he said, only 70
percent has been cured because of lack of follow-up on the parts
of the TB patients.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Alemnesh Wolde, head of the National
TB and Leprosy Control Program, said that shortage of anti-TB
medicinal drugs and health professionals in most of the regions
is one of the major problems encountered in the fight against the
disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-21 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Denies Military Buildup Along Iraqi Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwaiti army officer
Monday denied local reports that Kuwait is massing troops along
the Iraqi borders, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Ahmad Al-Rahmani, head of Moral Guidance and Public
Relations Department in the Kuwaiti army, said that "Kuwait is not
sending additional troops to the borders or raising the state of
readiness of the already existing forces on the northern borders."
</P>
<P>
Local Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Aam Monday quoted a senior
defense officer as saying that additional troops have joined the
units already stationed along the Kuwaiti-Iraqi borders. It
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rahmani said that since the end of the 1991 Gulf War, the
Kuwaiti army has been always ready to deal with any possible
actions by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that such news of sensitive nature should only be
taken from official sources "considering that security of the
homeland is an aim sought by all." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
