<HEADLINE> Ireland Supports Cyprus' EU Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Ireland supports Cyprus
application for European Union (EU) membership and would offer
its assistance to resolve the island's political problem,
visiting Irish Defense Minister Michael Smith said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with his Cypriot
counterpart Yiannakis Omirou, Smith said he discussed with Omirou
various issues of mutual concern, such as Cyprus' application
for accession to the EU, which "the Irish government supports."
</P>
<P>
"We are a small country ourselves, we remember the time when
we were applying for membership and received support from
different parts of Europe... and we gladly give that support to
your government in its effort to join the EU," the Irish defense
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that the developments in Northern Ireland and the peace
process were also discussed at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Our experiences would be gladly available to your government
and to the international community," he added.
</P>
<P>
Smith said that his current visit takes place on the occasion
of the 40th anniversary of his country's participation in
U.N. contingents, noting that Irish troops have been in about 30
countries during the period.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Omirou said he presented to Smith the Cypriot
government's views on the need for a political settlement on the
island, because the Cyprus problem remains a destabilizing factor
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Omirou said he also outlined his government's views on the
country's right to upgrade its defense, stressing, however,
Cyprus' commitment to demilitarization of the island under the
relevant proposals made by President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union
with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
