<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Countries Ratify Joint Development Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) approved a joint and comprehensive development
strategy here Monday to meet challenges for the next century.
</P>
<P>
The 2000-2025 strategy was adopted at the seventh session of
the GCC Ministerial Committee for Planning and Development, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of Planning Ali Moussa Al-Moussa said the
document, which will be presented at the upcoming GCC summit in
December, offers an objective evaluation of natural, regional and
international challenges the GCC member states will face in the
economic, social, political and security fields.
</P>
<P>
Al-Moussa, who is also Minister of State for Administrative
Development Affairs, said the document drew up broad lines to deal
with these challenges in the first quarter of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The needed institutional, legislative and technical mechanisms
to put the strategy into effect are also detailed in the
document, he said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting also discussed proposals of GCC planning
undersecretaries over mechanisms of coordination and data
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance set up
in 1981, groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Experts Urged to Sensitize Public About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
Monday called on the country's computer experts to take a lead in
sensitizing the public about the impending threat of computers'
failure to work after December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Education Minister Godfrey Miyanda when
launching the National Library Week at the University of Zambia
in the capital city, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda said that librarians, information technology
professionals and computer experts must discover and list what
the threats and needs of Zambia may be regarding the impending
computer collapse by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
He urged the professionals to put together, in simple
languages, what people can expect and how they may prepare
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda wondered why there was little being said about the
problem in the country's media. He attributed the silence on the
matter to little information available on the subject.
</P>
<P>
On the library system, the minister said it was saddening to
note that Zambia, despite being one of the first countries to
attain political independence in the continent, had no national
library system.
</P>
<P>
He noted his ministry is doing everything possible to promote
the development of libraries in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
