<HEADLINE> Romania, Kazakhstan to Develop Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Romania
and Kazakhstan Monday insisted on the importance of developing
commercial exchanges between their countries by the Euro-Asian
shipping corridor "the Modern Silk Road" program in the future.
</P>
<P>
President of Kazakhstan Nursultan Nazarbayev arrived in Romania
Sunday evening on a two-day official visit at the invitation of
his Romanian counterpart, Emil Constantinescu.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first of its kind since the two countries
established diplomatic ties in 1992, is aimed at promoting
bilateral political relations and trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the official talks, the two presidents approached
various issues of bilateral cooperation between the two countries,
mainly on the Modern Silk Road project, which establishes the oil
transport route from Caucasus to Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
President Constantinescu said, "There is the political will for
cooperation as well as the required legal framework which are to
be further developed."
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu said he had accepted Nazarbayev's invitation to
visit Kazakhstan, showing that this target belonged to the
strategic line of Romania's foreign policy, which stressed on the
development of its relations with Central Asian countries, next to
its European integration and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Kazakh president held lunch talks with
Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile and met with the president of
the upper chamber and the speaker of the lower chamber of
Romania's parliament.
</P>
<P>
After official talks, a series of bilateral documents, among
which a convention on the avoidance of double taxation, a
convention on consular ties and a statement on the development of
friendship and cooperative relations as well as an agreement on
cultural cooperation were signed in the presence of the two
presidents.
</P>
<P>
"The accords the Romanian and Kazakh sides signed are aimed at
preparing a framework to enable the development of the bilateral
relations on all levels," said Nazarbayev after the signing
ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Grand Jury Testimony Aired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Television stations in the
United States Monday broadcast the four-hour videotape of
President Bill Clinton's testimony in the Monica Lewinsky affair
before a grand jury on August 17.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives Judiciary Committee
simultaneously released the videotape along with some 3,200 pages
of Lewinsky case evidence, including Lewinsky's account of her
encounters with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton gave the testimony from the Map Room of the White House
by video link to a court house last month.
</P>
<P>
Republicans, who dominate the House of Representatives, say the
American people have the right to see the tape, to judge for
themselves whether Clinton lied to the grand jury. Many Democrats
say their real motive is to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
In his testimony, Clinton said, "It's an embarrassing and
personally painful thing."
</P>
<P>
The videotape of Clinton's testimony began playing unedited on
some televisions across America shortly before 9:30 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry called the videotape
release "rank partisanship" and said most of the materials being
made public were irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
The tape portrayed Clinton as sometimes angry at prosecutors'
questions and other times expressing bitterness at how the Paula
Jones lawsuit precipitated Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's
criminal investigation of the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
A two-volume set of evidence was delivered to lawmakers this
morning, then made public.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president was at the United Nations in New York.
His speech on combating terrorism got a standing ovation -- "the
warmest and most enthusiastic reception" he has received in six
U.N. speeches, said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. He said
Clinton didn't watch the video.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said the videotape showed Clinton refusing to discuss
intimate details of his relationship "despite repeated efforts by
Mr. Starr and his prosecutors to browbeat and badger him into
doing so."
</P>
<P>
McCurry said, "That the president's conduct does not rise to
the level of an impeachable offense should now be clear to
everyone."
</P>
<P>
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, a Democrat, said it was
"unfortunate" that Republicans insisted on releasing the tape. As
for its impact, he said, "how damaging is not something anybody
can assess right now."
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, campaigning in South Carolina,
kept quiet about the matter. Asked what the president should do,
Gingrich was quoted by news reports as saying, "I don't want to
get into that." 
</P>
</TEXT>
