<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Lifts Third-Degree Flood Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Belgium on Monday lifted the
third-degree warning of natural disaster for its last community
and started compensating for flood-hit regions.
</P>
<P>
The Nethe river valley was the last community in the country to
lift the warning that had been issued Monday last week when the
water level in most rivers in northeastern Belgium rose to surpass
the flood levels of 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Finance Minister Herman van Rompuy told the press
Monday that a total of 1.2 billion Belgian francs (34.2 million
U.S. dollars) would be available from the country's disaster
relief funds to compensate for the damages sustained by the people
in the 167 communities, or a third of the communities of the
country, that had been submerged by flood waters that were waist
deep in some places.
</P>
<P>
The water levels in the rivers Ambleve, Vesdre, Hoegne, Demer
and Meuse rose quickly after days of torrential rains in the
northeastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Continuous rains, that started late last month and kept on and
off for most of the past two and a half weeks, were attributed to
the unusually warmer waters in the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
When currents of cold-air masses run into hot-air masses rising
above the North Sea, they combine and produce rainfalls.
</P>
<P>
Third-degree warnings are given in case of natural catastrophe
by Belgium's provincial authorities that are then entitled to
demand military and specialized assistance if need arise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
