<HEADLINE> Ghana Works for Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ghana Environmental
Resources Management Project started in 1991 as the vehicle for
the implementation of the a National Environmental Action Plan
has born fruits, the Pan African News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has developed and implemented a 10-year environmental
education strategy while 105 district assemblies have been
assisted to prepare their local environmental action plans, the
Pan African News Agency quoted Executive Director of Ghanaian
Environmental Protection Agency Peter Acquah as saying.
</P>
<P>
The project has made a breakthrough as far as land information
system is concerned, said Acquah at a seminar in Accra last week.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a nationwide water quality monitoring is being
conducted in order to develop a stream-water quality standard for
major water bodies in the country, said Acquah.
</P>
<P>
In spite of these achievements, he said, "our main concern is
how to sustain what has been accomplished so far and how best to
address the key emerging environmental problems in the country."
</P>
<P>
The national environmental action plan includes the
development and support of a program to combat soil degradation
and erosion and to prevent further destruction of the fragile
resources in the coastal zone.
</P>
<P>
Ghana lost an estimated four percent of its gross domestic
product (GDP) or 41.7 billion Cedis (about 18.5 million U.S.
Dollars) in 1988 as a result of environmental degradation, said
Acquah.
</P>
<P>
The official said that losses resulting from the
activities of agriculture, forestry, industry and mining sectors
"imposed a strong case for taking effective action to reduce
them."  
</P>
</TEXT>
