<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Calls for World Support to Resolve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime
Minister Frederick Sumaye Monday appealed to the international
community to support the efforts made by regional leaders to
bring peace in the Great Lakes Region.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with former French President Valery Giscard
D'estaing in Dar es Salaam, Sumaye appealed to the international
community to extend material support to the countries in the
region which have been shouldering the burden of refugees from
the war-torn countries for a long period.
</P>
<P>
The refugee burden hinders the political and socio-economic
development in those countries and has negative impact on their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye said that the restoration of peace is in the interest
of the people of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) as well
as those in the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in the DRC has forced thousands of refugees in
the country to flee to Tanzania, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that Tanzania, together with other Great Lakes
countries, is trying to end the strife in the DRC through peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 5,000 refugees from the DRC have flowed into
Tanzania since the Tutsi-led rebels took up arms on August 2 to
fight against the government troops loyal to DRC President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are accommodated at the Nyarugusu refugee camp
in west Tanzania's Kigoma Region.  
