<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Qatari liquefied gas has gained access to the
U.S. market, the United Arab Emirates Arabic Al Itihad reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Qatar Liquefied Gas company signed a contract recently with
the U.S. Duke Energy firm, general manager of the Qatari gas
company Faisal Mohamed Al Sweidi said.
</P>
<P>
Faisal said Qatari liquefied gas has obtained markets in Japan,
Spain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is the third richest state in natural gas reserves in the
world following Iran and Russia.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government is encouraging local and
foreign companies to bid for an electric light rail system project
from downtown Amman to Zarqa, some 20 kilometers northeast to the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The 26-kilometer double track electrified standard gauge line
will cost 28 million Jordanian dinars (about 40 million U.S.
dollars), the semi-official Jordan Times reported.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) approved a
joint and comprehensive development strategy here Monday to meet
challenges for the next century.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of Planning Ali Moussa Al-Moussa said the
document, which will be presented at the upcoming GCC summit in
December, offers an objective evaluation of natural, regional and
international challenges the GCC member states will face in the
economic, social, political and security fields.
</P>
<P>
Al-Moussa, who is also Minister of State for Administrative
Development Affairs, said the document drew up broad lines to deal
with these challenges in the first quarter of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The needed institutional, legislative and technical mechanisms
to put the strategy into effect are also detailed in the
document, he said. 
</P>
