<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Proof Shows the Blind Hear Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian researchers have
produced new evidence supporting the popular belief that blind
people hear better than people who can see, according to a report
from the latest issue of Nature.
</P>
<P>
Franco Lepore and colleagues at the University of Montreal
compared eight blind people, three partially blind people and 36
people with normal vision. The blind people could locate the
origin of sounds as well as the sighted people, but did better
than the sighted people when one ear was plugged--the tougher of
the tasks, because people typically use slight differences in the
way sounds reach each ear to pinpoint the origin.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said their findings resolve a long-standing
controversy in that they provide behavioral evidence totally blind
individuals have better auditory ability than sighted people,
allowing them to compensate for their loss of vision.
</P>
<P>
But however as for how blind people's hearing might become
superior remains unknown, although there is evidence suggesting
that their brains reorganize to apply brain power that would
normally be used fro vision to hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Fall but off Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets finished
off their worst levels for the day as investors took heart from a
mild rebound on Wall Street after early declines.
</P>
<P>
The Dow was able to cut an early 175 point deficit to a 100 point
loss where it held steady during the Clinton videotape. But the FTSE
100 still closed at a new low for the year, down 65.3 at 4990.3.
</P>
<P>
The index had traded much lower earlier in the session on worries
about Asian market falls and after a profits warning from music
giant EMI.
</P>
<P>
The wait for the release of U.S. President Bill Clinton's
testimony to the Congressional Grand Jury kept the market uneasy all
day. Fears that his administration could be dragged down added
political uncertainty to already fragile markets.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 has fallen below the 5000 level twice since the
start of the year, once in January and again on September 11.
</P>
<P>
The drop had enough momentum to take the index briefly below 4900
before support was triggered.
</P>
<P>
Both the weakest point in the session, 4899.6, and the close were
the lowest since the first week of December 1997. However, London
shares managed to outperform other European markets.
</P>
<P>
The German DAX and the Paris CAC indices registered falls of
nearly 6 percent before levelling off to a 3.5 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
Analysts point out that while the Footise lagged continental
markets on their rapid rise in the first half of the year, it was
also lagging the declines.
</P>
<P>
Signs of a slowing UK economy have been a brake on the upside,
but the market's cautious attitude also meant that there was less
froth in the FTSE once global markets were shaken out.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Xetra Dax regained the 4400 level having
dropped to a session low of 4347.65. The index finished 184.24 lower
on the day at 4439.13.
</P>
<P>
Investors were also worried about the fall of the U.S. dollar
against the German mark. Export-sensitive car stocks were down
sharply.
</P>
<P>
Analists also said the OneWorld global airline alliance would be a
formidable contender to the existing Star Alliance that includes
Lufthansa.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares also pulled off the day's worst levels as
the Dow Jones stabilized. The CAC-40 finished 122.57 lower at
3342.65.  
</P>
</TEXT>
