<HEADLINE> Blair Emphasizes International Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister
Tony Blair said on Monday that high-level international
collaborative effort is the only way to tackle the complex
economic problems now facing the world.
</P>
<P>
"We face many challenges, but none more immediate than the
contagion of recession spreading from those countries currently in
difficulty to affect the wider world economy," he told the 53rd
U.N. General Assembly which started annual debate this morning.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that new mechanisms set up to deal with the
problems as "the absence of proper financial structures and
disciplines in individual countries will be punished by the
markets sooner or later".
</P>
<P>
According to Blair, such mechanisms should provide:
</P>
<P>
-- rules to encourage greater transparency in international and
national financial dealings;
</P>
<P>
-- better supervision and regulation of financial operators;
</P>
<P>
-- adequate resources for the international financial
institutions to deal with short-term liquidity problems;
</P>
<P>
-- structural reform programs for countries in difficulty which
take proper account of the social effects of restructuring.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain, the current chairman of the G8, will play its
full part in ensuring the necessary fresh look at the
international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
Blair said the European Union has been committed to zero
tariffs for the least developed countries by the year 2000, and he
urged all developed nations to follow suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
