<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Attend Commonwealth Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister
Ignatius Olisemeka will attend the meeting of the Commonwealth
Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) taking place on October 8-9 in
London.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the dialogue between the Commonwealth and
the military regime of General Abdulsalami Abubakar, who will
meet Commonwealth Secretary-General Emeka Anyaoku Wednesday on
his way to attend the U.N. General Assembly in New York, the Pan
African News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth in 1995 after
the then government of General Sani Abacha executed author Ken
Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth then established the CMAG to monitor the
development of human rights in Nigeria and to make
recommendations to the Commonwealth as to wether or not and when
to restore Nigeria's membership.
</P>
<P>
Past dialogue between Nigeria and the CMAG has proved
fruitless, while Nigeria has been refused opportunities to defend
itself at several CMAG meetings.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth had threatened to expel Nigeria for good if
its human rights record has no major improvement by 1996 but had
delayed from taking actions for several times.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Nigeria and the Commonwealth has improved
since Abubakar took office in June, as the new leader's
reconciliation effort and commitment to democratization have
received wide applaud in the West.
</P>
<P>
"The Commonwealth has been impressed with the actions taken
so far by the authorities in Nigeria to ensure a speedy and
workable transition to a credible democracy," Anyaoku was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A Commonwealth delegation visited Nigeria last week, during
which it offered to help the country's new Independent Electoral
Commission to conduct various elections under the Abubakar's new
transiton to civil rule program that will end on May 29, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
