<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Tea Prices Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 21 (Xinhua) --Kenya's Tea prices remained
firm on thin supply at the latest weekly export auction at the
Indian Ocean port of Mombasa, said a report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Quantities are normally low this time of the year. Because of
this, we expect prices to continue quite firm," said the report
quoting Richard Surrey, Chief of the Tea Brokers Association.
</P>
<P>
"Quality was also about maintained," he said, adding that
there was strong and improved demand at the auction last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Britain remained the main buyers. Purchases were
also made by Egypt, Sudan, Yemen and other Middle East countries.
Somalia bought lower grade teas.
</P>
<P>
Surrey said that traders from Iran and Pakistan who dealt with
Afghanistan found it difficult to operate because of the
political crisis there. Some had scaled down their purchases but
that had not unduly upset the market.
</P>
<P>
The Russian financial crisis had not affected Kenyan tea
sales because traditionally there were minimal purchases of
Kenyan tea by Russian traders, he added.
</P>
<P>
Premium grades Brighter Pekoes One (BP1s) rose by 5-20 U.S.
cents following quality. It gained more on selected BP1 lines.
Mediums were steady to 10 cents higher. Lower mediums and
plainer grades rose by five to 20 cents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
