<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's BA Announces Formation of Biggest Airline Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- British Airways has announced
the creation of the biggest airline network in the world.
</P>
<P>
BA and its US partner American Airlines (AA) are forming
alliances with airlines around the world, including Qantas of
Australia, Canadian Airlines International and Cathay Pacific of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
However, the alliance has prompted criticism from competitors
that they will be squeezed out with passengers paying more with
lower service standards.
</P>
<P>
Together the new network, "Oneworld", will become a dominant
force in the global airline industry.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific is set to land a place in the new global network.
Six other airlines, Japan Airlines, Iberia of Spain, Maersk Air of
Denmark, GB Airways of Britain, Finn Air and American West, are
expected to be involved in the partnership.
</P>
<P>
The five main partners will serve around 800 destinations and fly
more than 160 million passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
Customers will only have to purchase one ticket to use different
airline networks to get to destinations across the world. The
airlines will also be able to co-ordinate their schedules to create
"seamless" travel for passengers.
</P>
<P>
The creation of such a dominant industry force could pose a
serious threat to smaller airlines, unable to compete effectively
with the new network, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
The creation of this large alliance, with many more airlines, may
find opposition among competition regulators and lengthen the
investigation into an even tighter alliance already proposed by BA
and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Richard Branson, head of Virgin Atlantic, was quoted by BBC as
saying that the alliance deals are effectively mergers and will not
be in the interest of the airline consumer.
</P>
<P>
"Cathay Pacific and British Airways control 83 percent of the
Hong Kong-London route. Qantas, Cathay and BA are getting together
and that means there will be no competition on the Australian
route," he said. "If there is no competition they can set fares as
they wish, cut staff, cut costs, it is certainly not in the
consumer's interests."
</P>
<P>
Thus, he called on governments to make sure airlines had to
compete or there will end up being no competition in the aviation
market.
</P>
<P>
However, BA chief executive Bob Ayling promised that Oneworld
would be competitive on ticket prices, saying that "as in the case
of BA and AA, we have antitrust immunity not to compete."
</P>
<P>
"Our customers have told us they want airlines to work together
to raise standards of service across the world. Oneworld will do
just that," he said.
</P>
<P>
The latest move is part of the rapid consolidation of the airline
industry, analysts observed. BA has already established links with
Air Liberte of France and Deutsche BA of Germany.
</P>
<P>
BA's move is a bid to take on the Star Alliance, a consortium of
airlines set up 18 months ago by United Airlines of the United
States and Lufthansa of Germany.
</P>
<P>
However the new alliance may take some time to come to fruition.
AA and BA announced their own proposed alliance in 1996 but they
have yet to win final regulatory approval from UK and U.S.
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Peter Mandelson, the UK Trade Secretary, is not expected to make
a decision on whether to sanction the tie up between BA and AA
before November, according to a BBC report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
