<HEADLINE> Iran Wants to See 2001 as "Year of Dialogue Among  Civilizations" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday
proposed the United Nations designate the year 2001 as the "Year
of Dialogue Among Civilizations," with the earnest hope that
through such a dialogue, the realization of universal justice and
liberty may be initiated.
</P>
<P>
The proposal came as Iranian President Mohammad Khatami was
delivering a speech at the two-week general debate of the 53rd
session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue would be a first step to face the changing world,
he said, expressing his hope that the United Nations would take
necessary measures to respond to this evolving global climate.
</P>
<P>
"Among the worthiest achievements of this century is the
acceptance of the necessity and significance of dialogue and
rejection of force, promotion of understanding in culture,
economic and political fields, and strengthening of the foundation
of liberty, justice and human rights," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the Iranian president discussed the crisis
between his country and Afghanistan with Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
With some 200,000 Iranian troops massed on the Afghan border
after the killing of nine Iranian diplomats by the armed faction
of Taliban supporters, Khatami was using his visit to the United
Nations to appeal for international pressure to restrain the
militia Taliban, which controls most of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly began a general debate on Monday, Khatami
was among speakers from 181 countries to take the floor on a wide
range of matters of international concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
