<HEADLINE> East African Bourse Expected to Emerge by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is expecting an East
Africa bourse to be launched by 2000 with three trading floors in
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, a Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE) report
for 1997 said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Jimnah Mbaru, Chief of the NSE, said in the annual report that
a unified regional stock exchange can help integrate and
harmonize the three economies, raise access to a greater pool of
resources and ease cross-border listing of securities.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign investors will also be attracted by a large capital
market," said Mbaru.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's bourse is the largest in east Africa. Uganda's has
opened with only a bond traded, and equity trading is now
forecast to start next January. Tanzania's bourse has two listed
companies.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan bourse officials believe that the year 2000 deadline
for the regional stock exchange will be met. But some analysts
said the time appears too short in view of the fact that the three
countries have to harmonize certain financial laws first.
</P>
<P>
So far, foreign investment in stocks is still banned in
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
