<HEADLINE> Shipment of Pakistani Aid Arrive in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A shipment of 14,000 tons
of rice in Pakistani aid to the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) arrived Tuesday in Nampo, a port city on the west
coast of the DPRK, the Korean Central News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The shipment is part of 30,000 tons of rice in a line of free
humanitarian aid extended by Pakistan to the DPRK this year.
</P>
<P>
In assisting the DPRK in overcoming difficulties arising from
natural disasters hitting the country over recent years, Pakistan
extended 5,000 tons of rice and relief supplies worth 160,000
U.S. dollars to the DPRK in 1996, and 2,000 tons of rice in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The KCNA said that Pakistan's extension of humanitarian aid to
the DPRK will encourage the DPRK people to overcome temporary
difficulties brought about by natural disasters and to fight for
realizing self-sufficiency in the supply of grains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
