<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Opinion polls conducted after U.S. television
showed President Bill Clinton's grand jury testimony in the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal showed Tuesday that the airing was less
damaging than his critics had predicted.
</P>
<P>
A Gallup poll conducted for CNN and USA Today showed that 66
percent of respondents still approved of the job Clinton is doing,
six points higher than the figure Sunday, the day before the
broadcast. The approval figure on the previous Sunday was 64
percent.
</P>
<P>
The same percentage rejected impeachment, but 39 percent
thought Clinton should resign, the poll showed. USA Today said 81
percent of respondents believed Clinton definitely or probably
lied under oath to the grand jury. (US-Clinton-Poll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SIEM REAP -- Leaders of Cambodia's three rival parties agreed
Tuesday in the northern town of Siem Reap to hold talks on the
formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders also agreed at their meeting that the new
National Assembly, or parliament, would convene on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Former senior co-premier Prince Norodom Ranariddh met
government leader Hun Sen, the co-premier who ousted him in July
last year. It was their first meeting since the incident.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the party leaders, including former finance
minister Sam Rainsy, now the head of a party bearing his name,
lined up with King Norodom Sihanouk who presided over the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen did not speak to reporters but senior member of his
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and minister without portfolio Sok
An said the atmosphere at the four-hour meeting was
good. (Cambodia-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea and Japan will begin critical rounds of
talks on a new fishery pact in Tokyo Wednesday, the Foreign
Affairs and Trade Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Japan Tuesday, Yun Byung-se, deputy director
general of the ministry's Asian and Pacific Affairs Bureau, said
South Korea and Japan could narrow their differences on most
contentious issues to work out a draft fishery accord which will
replace the 1965 fishing accord.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that South Korean Minister of Maritime Affairs
and Fisheries Kim Sun-kil is scheduled to meet with his Japanese
counterpart Shoichi Nakagawa Wednesday for the joint-fishing area
issue. The ministry used to say that the issue of where to
establish a joint fishing area should be decided at
ministerial-level negotiations. (SKorea-Japan-Fishery Talks)
</P>
</TEXT>
