<HEADLINE> Canada Provides Aid to Flood Victims in Southern Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Tuesday that
the Canadian International Development Agency will provide 150,000
Canadian dollars (97,500 U.S. dollars) to flood victims in
southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"Since the beginning of September, torrential downpours have
hit this region, killing close to 180 people and affecting another
1.2 million. We must provide assistance quickly to the victims to
prevent a further deterioration of their situation," said Canadian
International Cooperation Minister Diane Marleau in a release
issued here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian assistance, to be managed by the Pan American
Health Organization, will largely be used to control these risks
by giving those responsible for local health care services access
to well-digging equipment, handpumps, and chlorine tablets to
purify water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
