<HEADLINE> S. Korea, Japan Agree on Measures Against DPRK Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan would
work together against alleged proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached here Tuesday afternoon, the two
nations would maintain close cooperation to prevent the DPRK from
developing, producing and exporting long-rang missiles.
</P>
<P>
They would also enhance consultations and information exchange.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by South Korean Deputy Defense
Minister Lee Sang-hee and his Japanese counterpart Boru Kawajiri.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the DPRK launched a three-stage rocket to fly over
the Japanese territory and then place a satellite into orbit.
</P>
<P>
Japan, South Korea, and the United States alleged that the DPRK
launch of satellite has posed a grave threat to the security of
Northeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
