<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IS, ICTs to Provide More Jobs in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Information Society (IS)
and Information and Communication Technologies (ICTs) are expected
to provide Europe with more jobs, a senior European Commission
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by European Employment Commissioner
Padraig Flynn at an information technology conference in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The Information Society, the commissioner told conference
participants, is now the biggest industry in Europe and is growing
3 percent faster than the rest of the economy and is contributing
toward 15 percent of the overall economic growth in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The IS and ICTs created more than 300,000 jobs between 1995 and
1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
The European Information Technology Observatory estimated that
Europe will need between 1.5 million and 2 million new information
technology professionals in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
But the commissioner pointed to the fact that some European
Union member states had been cutting back on technical places in
universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
Flynn said: "We can and must do even better on making the link
between Information and Communication Technologies and the skills
the IS job requires and job creation."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said that the 1998 national employment action
plans showed that EU member states were still not taking enough
account of Information Society issues.
</P>
<P>
He told the conference participants that the commission, the
executive body of the 15-nation union, will have to look at the
issue while reviewing and strengthening the employment process
for 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops in Lesotho to Help Find Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and
Botswana's military intervention in Lesotho was to help find a
lasting political solution, not to enforce a military solution to
a political issue, South African Acting President Mangosuthu
Buthelezi said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of the intervention is to restore stability as
quickly as possible and to withdraw from the Kingdom of Lesotho
as soon as this has been achieved," Buthelezi said in a special
address to the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said the Southern African Development Community (SADC) had
made it clear that member states could not tolerate coups d'etat
in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We need to stress that the intervention by the SADC forces is
not intended to force the Lesotho parties to negotiate," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The solution to Lesotho's problems is the sovereign right of
the people of Lesotho to resolve in the manner that they choose."
</P>
<P>
He said he had been told that the parties in the conflict were
committed to ongoing negotiations, and had agreed to meet each
other on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said it was important that the multiparty talks
should take place in an appropriate environment underpinned by
stability which ordinarily should be established by the Lesotho
Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said repeatedly that the intervention was a SADC
operation, not South Africa's, and that it followed the failure
of SADC efforts to resolve the crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
He said he had authorized the troop deployment in his capacity
as acting president.
</P>
<P>
He had consulted SADC parties responsible for guaranteeing
Lesotho's democracy, although he had not been able to speak
directly with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who was
unavailable, and Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano, who had
left for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
He had also consulted President Nelson Mandela, who is in
Washington, and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 soldiers from South Africa and Botswana entered
Lesotho early Tuesday morning to try to restore order in
Lesotho's capital of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
At least three South African soldiers have been killed and 11
injured in clashes with Lesotho troops siding with opposition
party supporters.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho was plunged into anarchy when opposition protesters
forced stayaways and hijacked government vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They claim that the May 23 general election was rigged in
favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy and demand
fresh polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
