<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia: Major Parties Agree to Talk About New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of
Cambodia's three rival parties agreed Tuesday in the northern town
of Siem Reap to hold talks on the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders also agreed at their meeting that the new
National Assembly, or parliament, would convene on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Former senior co-premier Prince Norodom Ranariddh met
government leader Hun Sen, the co-premier who ousted him in July
last year. It was their first meeting since the incident.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the party leaders, including former finance
minister Sam Rainsy, now the head of a party bearing his name,
lined up with King Norodom Sihanouk who presided over the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen did not speak to reporters but senior member of his
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and minister without portfolio Sok
An said the atmosphere at the four-hour meeting was good.
</P>
<P>
"The relations between the leaders of the three parties seem to
be much better than before," Sok An told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The King said very clearly that all parties have to
participate in the National Assembly, but it's the right of the
parties to join or not to join the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Representing his FUNCINPEC party, Ranariddh said: "It was a
very good summit. We've said that all parties...will start
negotiations about the formation of a new government.
</P>
<P>
"I think definitely we have made progress instead of
stalemate," he said. "In spite of remaining problems, we have
agreed to go forward...but we still have a long way to go."
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy, whose parties came second and third
in the July election, rejected Hun Sen's election victory, saying
the CPP won through fraud and intimidation.
</P>
<P>
They mounted more than three weeks of protests against the
election results but called off the demonstrations and agreed to
talks last week, after coming under mounting pressure from the
King and the international community.
</P>
<P>
They also dropped a threat to boycott parliament after clashes
between their supporters and police caused the death of two
protesters.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen's CPP does not have the two-thirds of parliamentary
seats necessary to form a government alone. Hun Sen has offered to
bring both opposition parties, which control all remaining seats,
into a coalition but he has made clear he does not need Sam
Rainsy's party.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said Hun Sen presented the meeting with three
scenarios. The CPP could form a coalition with the FUNCINPEC
party, or it could amend the constitution to do away with the
two-thirds rule and govern alone, or it could simply extend the
life of the current government, the prince said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
