<HEADLINE> Typhoons Cause Economic Losses in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 34 million pesos
(790,000 U.S. dollars) worth of crops and livestock were destroyed
in the northern Philippines when two typhoons hit the country last
week, agriculture officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Joseph Estrada, Agriculture Secretary
William Dar said that as of Monday, the two typhoons, Emang and
Gading, caused huge production losses in seven provinces.
</P>
<P>
The typhoons, which pounded the northern island of Luzon during
the weekend, damaged more than 18,000 hectares of rice land,
causing a production loss of 13,500 metric tons of rice worth 32
million pesos (744,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Dar added in his report that the typhoons likewise wrought
havoc on 66 hectares of fishponds, with 2.3 million pesos (53,000
dollars) worth of fish destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Dar also reported that the typhoons caused a breakdown in
communication facilities in the western part of Pangasinan
province and rendered impassable all roads leading to that area.
</P>
</TEXT>
