<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Set to Save Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
Congress agreed Tuesday night to exert all efforts to save
Philippine Airlines (PAL) domestic routes regardless of the
results of a referendum among PAL employees.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesperson Jerry Barican told reporters that one
option eyed by President Joseph Estrada and lawmakers is a 1.5
billion pesos (34.9 million U.S. dollars) bridge financing scheme
to bankroll the airline's operations for the next three months.
</P>
<P>
The bridge financing plan, if approved, will come from
government financing institutions that are investors in PAL, with
these institutions getting first crack at PAL payments after three
months.
</P>
<P>
"(Our) principal agreement is that the domestic lines of PAL
are far important to the economy to be allowed not to continue,"
Barican told reporters after a meeting between Estrada and
congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the participants at the meeting also agreed to
meet again at noon Wednesday to discuss the government's next move
following the results of the PAL referendum.
</P>
<P>
PAL union members voted Tuesday on whether to agree on an offer
from the PAL management to save the airlines from its current
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the offer, the trade union will get 20 percent of PAL
shares in exchange for a 10-year suspension of its collective
bargaining agreement, with every employee receiving 60,000 shares
worth 300,000 pesos (6,976 dollars).
</P>
<P>
PAL management scheduled the closure of the airlines for
midnight Wednesday after the union refused to accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
Economists here warned that the impending shutdown of PAL, the
country's national flag carrier, is expected to considerably
affect the Philippine economy since the country is composed of
more than 7,000 islands and PAL is vital to local transportation.
</P>
</TEXT>
