<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Naturally Preserved Body Mystifies Chinese Experts (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The body of an elderly
Chinese woman who passed away six years ago at the age of 87
remains in a natural state of preservation in the home of her
children.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 people, including a number of famous medical
experts, scientists and scholars, have visited the home to view
the body of Zhou Fengchen, who was born on November 2, 1905, in
Xianghe County, north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily, China's leading daily newspaper, had
covered the story extensively.
</P>
<P>
The natural state of preservation of the body of Zhou Fengchen
continues to pose a mystifying question for modern science. Zhou
lived in Huzhuangzi Village of Xianghe County, located some 52 km
from Beijing, the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Zhou's heart stopped beating at 22:45 on the evening of
November 24. 1992, and 15 minutes later she was pronounced dead by
a Beijing doctor.
</P>
<P>
"My grandmother's body remained in a normal state for about
five days, with the elasticity of the muscles remaining for even
longer," said Yang Xueqiang, the woman's oldest grandson.
</P>
<P>
"Fluids and gases oozed from the body for about a month before
the metamorphosis ended. The body has since remained in a state of
natural preservation," said Yang, an officer in the People's
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that all changes occurred under natural
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The woman's body is now housed in a dwelling typically found in
the north China countryside. The body has not been embalmed and no
special protective measures have been introduced.
</P>
<P>
However, a glass shroud protects the body from dust. A delicate
fragrance can be detected when the shroud is removed and the body
is free of odors associated with decomposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Naturally Preserved Body Mystifies Chinese Experts (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Body muscles have shriveled and hardened, while the hands and
feet have retained their natural skin color and are in excellent
condition. The luster of the woman's natural white hair remains,
and an oily substance slowly surfaces from the woman's bronzed
forehead.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jing, former director of the management office of the
Chairman Mao Memorial Hall who has made significant contributions
to maintaining the body of Mao Zedong, commented that the
mysterious phenomenon resemble mummification.
</P>
<P>
However, many experts stress the body has not been mummified.
</P>
<P>
"Mummies emit an easily detectable odor, quite unlike the
woman's body," said Lu Jinchuan, a famous scholar on traditional
Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
In November of 1997, a group of experts conducted an extensive
examination of the body and the findings were published in May
this year. The paper points out that the natural preservation of
bodies subject to natural temperatures and humidity is quite rare.
</P>
<P>
The authors of the paper, Li Shen and Zhang Ruijun, both
members of the team, pointed out that the causes of irregular
patterns on an electrocardiogram have not as yet been determined.
</P>
<P>
The story has attracted extensive attention and two related
seminars have been held in Xianghe and Beijing respectively over
the past six years. Nonetheless, the mystery remains
unanswered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Employment Bank in Bangladesh Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Employment Bank, the first
of its kind in Bangladesh, went into operation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Declaring the bank open at the Osmany Memorial Hall, Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina expressed her belief that the bank would
help create employment opportunities and integrate the youth force
into the country's economic development activities.
</P>
<P>
The bank would open up new opportunities for eradicating
poverty and helping build a happy and prosperous society, she
said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called for proper care and supervision to
help achieve the objective of the bank.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the bank was to help unemployed, educated
youths, but it would simultaneously extend loans to those who do
not have formal education but have skills to make a project
viable, officials said.
</P>
<P>
With an initial paid-up capital of 1 billion taka (about 21.28
million U.S. dollars), the bank would be able to give loans to
unemployed youths.
</P>
<P>
A loan of up to 50,000 taka (about 1,064 dollars) would not
require any guarantor, but all the borrowers would have to deposit
their academic certificates with the bank, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Of the paid-up capital, the government would provide 750
million taka (about 15.96 million dollars) with the rest coming
from local and foreign financial institutions, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
