<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Gasoline Price Fourth Highest Among OECD Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea ranked the fourth
highest in terms of gasoline prices among the 16 non-oil producing
countries of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
According to a survey on the OECD's non-producing countries
issued by the South Korean Ministry of Commerce, Industry and
Energy Tuesday, average gasoline prices in South Korea hit 1,224
won (0.915 U.S. dollar) per liter.
</P>
<P>
France ranked first with gasoline prices reaching 1.01 U.S.
dollars per liter, followed by Italy with 0.97 U.S. dollar and
Sweden with 0.968 U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's gasoline price is 0.129 U.S. dollar higher than
the average price of 0.786 U.S. dollar per liter among the OECD
non-oil producing countries, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the high gasoline price to the
competition among domestic oil refiners.
</P>
<P>
Since January this year, South Korea have raised the gasoline
prices several times due to won devaluation and other reasons.
Last Friday, the nation hiked the prices in a response to the rise
in traffic and basic taxes on fuel oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
