<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chaos in Lesotho as Foreign Troops Intervene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Looting and incidents
of arson and mob violence are taking place in the Lesotho capital
of Maseru as a combined force of South African and Botswanan
troops try to restore order in the city, South African Radio
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maseru residents are reported to be reacting angrily to the
intervention by the combined task force.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic gunfire is still being heard, and the city is covered
in a pall of smoke after several government buildings in the city
center have been apparently set on fire.
</P>
<P>
The houses of Foreign Minister Tom Thabane and Deputy Prime
Minister Kelebone Maope have been burnt down, Thabane told the
radio.
</P>
<P>
"A coup has really taken place."
</P>
<P>
Thabane said the government is in hiding, adding that he and
his colleagues are safe.
</P>
<P>
There is now an anti-South African sentiment in Lesotho, the
radio said. Mobs of youths are reported to be attacking vehicles
with south African registration numbers. South African
journalists have to use vehicles without registration plates.
</P>
<P>
The radio said South Africa's high commissioner in Maseru has
returned to South Africa under military guard.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force spokeswoman, Laverne
Machine, confirmed that three South African soldiers have been
killed in the fighting. Eleven others were believed to be
injured.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Joel Netshitenzhe told the radio that the
decision to send troops to Lesotho was made by the Southern
African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
South African acting President Mangosuthu Buthelezi gave the
nod to send contingents to Lesotho with consultation to President
Nelson Mandela and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Both Mandela and Mbeki are abroad.
</P>
<P>
The 800-strong troops of South Africa and Botswana Tuesday
morning stormed the royal palace in Maseru, where a number of
opposition supporters are reported to have taken refuge.
</P>
<P>
The palace is now under the control of the foreign troops
and the palace gates have been re-opened and some of the
opposition supporters, who had taken refuge in the palace, left
the building.
</P>
<P>
The task force troops have now turned their attention to the
city center where looters are reported to be causing havoc, said
the radio.  
</P>
</TEXT>
