<HEADLINE> Annual Pacific Rim Forum Opens in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The annual meeting of the
Pacific Rim Forum was held today in Shanghai, China's largest
trade and financial center, at a time when growing concern about
the negative impact of financial crisis in Southeast Asia is
sweeping the world.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 well-known political and economic figures from 18
countries and regions attended today's meeting, including former
Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating and Supachai Panitch Pakdi,
Thai deputy Prime Minister and Commerce minister.
</P>
<P>
Participants exchanged views on strategies for multinational
cooperation in the Asia-Pacific Region, trade and investment
opportunities in China, economic globalization and lessons to be
learned from the financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Vice Mayor Chen Liangyu said that China will continue
to seek foreign investment and will participate in globalization
of the world economy, while at the same time improving its ability
to resist economic instability resulting from financial turmoil in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the Chinese government has adopted effective measures
to counter the effects of the crisis, including increasing
investment, encouraging domestic demand and steadfastly
maintaining the stability of the Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Shanghai's export volume grew by 10.4 percent
over the past eight months, with the city's gross domestic product
up by 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chen also pointed out that Shanghai's GDP is expected to end
the year at 10 percent. 
</P>
