<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Buddhist Sacred Mountain Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nowadays, Jiuhua Mountains, one
of China's four sacred mountains for Chinese Buddhists, looks like
a huge construction site, with many hotels and shops being built.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have invested heavily in the Buddhist place,
in east China's Anhui Province, in an effort to turn it into a
major tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
The projects include a 60-million-yuan-worth, 22.4-km-long
highway to link Jiuhua Mountains with neighboring Huangshan
Mountains, and a 26-million-yuan-worth cable-way, which will be
the first on-track cable-way in China.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, preparations for erecting a 99-m-tall bronze
statue of the Buddha are underway, which would cost some 400
million yuan. "The statue would be a symbol of Jiuhua Mountains,"
says Huang Yi, director of the Jiuhua Mountains Scenic Zone
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Most of the funds will come from the sales of entry tickets and
donations from pilgrims, the official says. In 1997, the scenic
zone earned some 240 million yuan from tourists and related
industries, while the temples received at least 50 million yuan in
cash from pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
Both religious and tourist activities have boomed in the
Jiuhua Mountains Scenic Zone, since it was opened up to tourists
in 1979. The number of tourists and pilgrims it receives has been
rising year by year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, 1.3 million people including 18,000 foreign
nationals visited the religious and scenic place, which is one of
the 44 national scenic reserves in the country.
</P>
<P>
Jiuhua Mountains has been a Buddhist sacred site for 1,500
years, says Master Shi Shengming of the Baijingtai
Temple. According to historical records, Buddhist monks first
arrived in the area as early as in the year 401,
</P>
<P>
Buddhism boomed in the area during the Ming and Qing dynasties
(1368-1911), when there were over 300 Buddhist temples and more
than 4,000 Buddhist monks and nuns.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are nine temples under state protection and 30
under provincial protection, and many valuable religious relics
are kept in these temples, including some Buddhist sutras. One
scripture was written by a monk in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644)
with his blood.
</P>
<P>
There are four bodies of monks that have remained intact for
many years like mummies after they died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
