<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Developing Credit Card Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China will give more emphasis
to the credit card business, which is expected to give a boost to
the Chinese economy by allowing individual credit, stimulating
consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
This view is universally agreed on by card experts and
officials who were present today at an international seminar on
the credit card industry, and who have asked the state to develop
the card business as an independent industry and to develop credit
cards rather than the debit cards that have mainly been used so
far, so that Chinese use the cards more as electronic wallets.
</P>
<P>
Credit cards, which allow overdrafts, are still rare in China
and this has posed difficulties for the nation's card
market. China needs to introduce more credit cards, which could
solve the problem of deflation and give the economy a boost by
encouraging buying on credit and installment buying, according to
Wu Jinglian, a prominent economist.
</P>
<P>
Wu also said that the card market is huge because more Chinese
need to buy goods in installments these days. Expensive goods like
houses and cars also mean a need for credit.
</P>
<P>
The credit card is the best way for banks to provide individual
credit and it is only with such services that the card business
can develop as an independent industry, Wu says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Credit Card Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The credit card business has always been regarded as
subordinate to traditional banking services and not an independent
one. The government introduced cards to encourage the use of
electronic money, which is more convenient, and commercial banks
wanted to attract more deposits through the use of debit cards.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, China had issued 90 million cards that were
responsible for more than 1.6 trillion yuan in business annually.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese card market faces problems of slow growth
in the number of cards issued every year because it is not an
independent industry, according to Zhang Weidong, general manger
of Bank of China's retail banking department.
</P>
<P>
In addition, commercial banks' card business is in disarray and
each bank has hundreds of branch banks that are authorized to
issue their own cards. The poorly-managed card business has wasted
a great deal of hardware and the electronic network.
</P>
<P>
"We can not even figure out whether our bank's card business is
making a profit or a loss," Zhang comments.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 BOC branches have the right to issue cards, but
that figure may shrink to 200 this year as the bank tries to
improve the card business, which badly needs to be separated from
the banking business, with a unified and strengthened management,
says Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The bottom line is that the card business needs to be developed
as an independent industry, rather than as a type of banking
business, according to card experts and officials at the seminar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
