<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Parties Launch Policy Blitz, Polls Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) --Australia's Liberal and Labor
parties Tuesday launched a policy blitz on the environment, family
policy, education, justice and primary industries with the latest
opinion polls showing the October 3 election still on a
knife-edge.
</P>
<P>
With opinion polls showing the two major parties neck and neck,
preference votes, including those from the Democrats and Greens,
will be important to the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
Labor has announced a 95.6 million Australian dollars (55.92
million U.S. dollars) environment package. The opposition party
has also pledged to oppose the damming of West Australia's Fitzroy
River and prohibit the handover of Kakadu and Uluru national parks
to the Northern Territory Government.
</P>
<P>
Labor unveiled its campaign pitch to win back women and young
families by announcing a boost to childcare funding as the
centerpiece of its 390 million Australian dollars (228.15 million
U.S. dollars) family policy.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition, on the other hand, announced 90 million
Australian dollars (52.65 million U.S. dollars) for the
environment, to be funded from its proposed further 16 percent
sale of Telstra, the public telecommunication company. The policy
is to target urban problems, including air quality, polluted urban
waterways, waste and chemicals management.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard Tuesday touched upon the foreign
policy in his campaign by announcing the creation of a prime
ministerial task force on reforming the world's financial
institutions and planning to use November's APEC meeting to help
lift the region out if its economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he would urge APEC leaders to be committed to the
so-called Basle core principles for effective banking supervision,
in a bid to strengthen Asian banking systems to prevent another
Asian financial meltdown from occurring.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Center for Independent Studies in Sydney, he
said the upcoming APEC leaders' meeting in Kuala Lumpur is an
important opportunity to pursue the goal of open markets and to
renew opportunities to reform.
</P>
<P>
Howard also revealed that he would set up a prime ministerial
task force of government and private sector representatives to
provide advice on reforming the world's financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Australia and the Asia-Pacific region needed to ensure their
voices were heard more clearly in the International Monetary Fund
and in talks on the future of the world's financial institutions,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Howard also welcomed calls from U.S. President Bill Clinton for
an international response to the world financial crisis, saying
the proposals deserved full support from the international
community.
</P>
<P>
But he called on Japan to get its economic house in order and
to develop more responsive decision-making structures as a top
priority.
</P>
<P>
The Australian's Newspoll Tuesday showed Labor still ahead of
the coalition by one point, despite a one-point drop in support
over the past week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
