<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loess Plateau Rehabilitation Project In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A great change has taken
place in a short a period of time thanks to a World Bank Loess
Plateau watershed rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shan, a 43-year-old farmer in the village of Zijinshan,
Pianguan County, is among the first farmers on the Loess Plateau
to benefit. In 1994, Wang used a World Bank loan of some 3,000
yuan to build 17 mu (about 1.14 ha.) of terraced land, increasing
per mu grain yield from 75 kg. to more than 250 kg.
</P>
<P>
"The yield of the original land was very low and we had to rely
on the weather for food," he explains, "When there was a drought,
we didn't have enough to eat."
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Shanxi used 37 million U.S. dollars in soft loans from
the World Bank, along with a Chinese government investment of 200
million yuan for the watershed rehabilitation project on 5,052
sq.km. of land in 67 townships in 8 counties, where 376,000 people
live.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi and the World Bank have designated two objectives for
the project: environmental protection and poverty alleviation,
reducing the sediment flow into the Yellow River and increasing
agricultural production and farmers' incomes.
</P>
</TEXT>
