<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sacked Minister: I Differ With President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Dismissed Zambian Minister of
Commerce, Trade and Industry Enoch Kavindele has said he differed
with president Frederick Chiluba on the issue of reducing duty on
soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
The Post newspaper Tuesday quoted him as saying here Monday
that at a meeting in June this year he explained to Chiluba the
importance of reducing duty because many jobs would be lost if
Zambia bottlers closed down due to losses.
</P>
<P>
He said he also told Chiluba that many companies depend on the
Coca Cola company for business.
</P>
<P>
"On June 11, 1998 President Chiluba called us to State House
over the same matter and I explained to the president the
importance of reducing duty. I said that too many jobs would be
lost and that many companies like Kapiri Glass Company depended
on Zambia Bottlers," said the former minister, who was sacked
Monday in a cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
However, he said he will remain an ordinary member of the
ruling party and have no intentions of joining other parties.
</P>
<P>
Kavindele repeated Sunday his warning that about 19,000 jobs
will be lost and Zambia's economy will be distorted greatly if
the country's Finance Ministry does not reduce excise duty
quickly on soft drinks to avert an impending closure of Zambia
Bottlers, the manufacturer of Coca Cola products in the country.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that his ministry has informed the
Finance Ministry that the current 25 percent excise duty on
carbonated drinks is not viable and recommended that it be
reduced to five percent.
</P>
<P>
In May this year, the government promised to reduce duty on
Coca Cola for Zambia Bottlers but has not honored its promise to
date. The company however has almost doubled the price of its
product from 500 Kwacha (0.25 U.S.Dollar) to 900 Kwacha.
</P>
<P>
The price increase has invitably slumped the demand for the
products while retailers in some border areas have started
importing soft drinks from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Last week the company suspended its production and threatened
to pull out of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
But the country's finance minister branded the company as a
blackmailer which has for a long time been evading tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
