<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Corruption Scandal Puts Thai Coalition in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua -- A corruption scandal involving
Health Ministry officials has put Thailand's coalition government
at crossroads where it has to decide whether to bring in new
partners to ensure stability.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Rakkiat Sukthana submitted his resignation last
week, and was followed by his deputy Thirawat Siriwansan who
stepped down Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two men, belonging to the Social Action Party (SAP),
resigned over a full-blown scandal involving the Health Ministry
accused of re-selling over-priced pharmaceutical products worth
millions of dollars at the market.
</P>
<P>
Official investigation over the alleged irregularities is still
in progress, and that means the SAP will be in an even worse
situation. Not only were the two cabinet members disgraced by the
outrage, but two other SAP MPs who serve as their advisers are
expected to face legal troubles of their own if more evidence is
uncovered about wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
With the resignation of Rakkiat and Thirawat, the SAP is at a
low ebb of its standing in the coalition and does not have much
bargaining power left now despite some word of personal support
from Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai who said the other day that the
tainted officials did not mean the SAP was a bad lot.
</P>
<P>
The SAP's disgrace also weakens the already fragile coalition
led by Chuan's Democratic Party. Chuan reportedly is lobbying
support for bringing in the Social Development Party (SDP) into
the coalition to ensure stability.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, the Democrats and the SDP were said to be on
the verge of striking a partnership deal, with the latter
reportedly softening its cabinet quota demands.
</P>
<P>
Bringing in the SDP, with some 51 votes in the 393-member
Parliament, would mean that the government commanded a very
comfortable majority in the House and there might be fewer scary
scenarios about sharp shortfalls of votes when crucial bills are
presented to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
But the Democrats' allies, in a bid to protect their
ministerial seats, are united in blocking the entry of the SDP,
thus rendering a cabinet reshuffle impossible at present. A
government official said the SDP has to wait a little longer
before it can enter the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The allies, fearing that Chuan could dump any of them and turn
to the SDP, assured Chuan of unwavering support and discipline at
future crucial House meetings. "We'd like to give you our
encouragement and our pledge to see to it that all votes are
accounted for," a source quoted Agricultural Minister Pongpol
Adireksarn as saying. Such commitment was echoed by other cabinet
members.
</P>
<P>
In return, Chuan accepted the allies' suggestion that it is not
the best time to bring in the SDP at present. He also decided to
keep the scandal-tainted SAP in the coalition at all costs, even
the party had a much less favorable cabinet quota.
</P>
<P>
Chuan denied being pressured by the allies to reject the SDP.
"It has been my principle that a consensus among the partners is
needed before such a big change," Chuan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said courting the SDP, with its long-standing
reputation as a prima donna and unsubstantiated claims of
excellence in economic management, and mollifying the present
partners could mean double jeopardy for the Chuan coalition.
</P>
<P>
Chuan knows he has to continue his balancing act -- pacifying
nervous allies while keeping the SDP hopeful over the possibility
of joining the ruling bloc in the future, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
