<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Rules on Family Planning for Transient Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's State Family Planning
Commission (SFPC) today published a revised version of its
Regulations on Family Planning for the Transient Population, whose
purpose is to reduce the number of unregistered births and control
population growth.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will take effect January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The number of transient people in China reached 100 million by
1997, more than 3 times the 1982 figure. The increase has put
great pressure on family planning in both urban and rural areas,
says Zhang Weiqing, minister in charge of SFPC, who explains
that "transient population" refers to people who leave the place
where they are registered as permanent residents to work or start
families elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Governments of areas where transient people reside have the
major responsibility for family planning, which includes checking
marriage and family status, providing contraceptives and birth
control services, and dealing with those who have violated family
planning regulations, according to the revised regulations.
</P>
<P>
People involved in forging or selling family planning
certificates or gaining such certificates fraudulently will be
dealt with by family planning departments above the county level
and may be fined up to 1,000 yuan (120 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Anyone found providing fake certificates of marriage or family
status will have to return to their hometown to apply for a proper
certificate and may be fined.
</P>
<P>
Units or individuals who employ transient people are
responsible for their family planning and should have an
inspection by local government and neighborhood committee. Owners
of houses where transient people live have to help promote family
planning.
</P>
<P>
Some of the regulations are meant to protect the rights of
transient people. One regulation says that birth control fees for
married transient people will be paid by the organizations they
are working for or by the local government of the area where they
have registered as permanent residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
