<HEADLINE> Tension Rises in North, East Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA,Sept 22 (Xinhua) -- Jose Joao Manuel "Jota",
spokesman for the general staff of the Angolan armed forces, said
here Tuesday that the military situation in the northern and
eastern part of the country is "rather tense."
</P>
<P>
In Uige and Malange provinces in the north and Lunda-Norte and
Lunda-Sul Provinces in the east, forces loyal to Jonas Savimbi,
chairman of the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA), have beefed up their military operations, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, the officer added, the government troops are still in
firm control of the situation and are ready for mopping-up in
certain areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fernando Jose Canga, deputy governor of Uige
Province, noted Monday that unidentified international airplanes
continued landing in the airport in Maquela do Zombo City, north
of the province, about 40 km from the border of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), to provide food and weapons for UNITA
forces stationed there.
</P>
<P>
In mid-September, UNITA forces occupied Damba and Maquela do
Zombo, two cities in north Uige, with the assistance of
Banyamulenge rebels from the DRC, and attacked heavily areas
around the two cities, killing and wounding several dozens of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
On September 16, UNITA forces ambushed a U.N. food convoy,
wounding three peacekeeping soldiers (one already dead), with the
rest ten still missing.
</P>
<P>
They also destroyed nine trucks and robbed the goods onboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
