<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Figures released by Dubai customs office showed
the United Arab Emirates imported 29.57 tonnes of gold in August,
21 percent more than in July.
</P>
<P>
But the figures indicated a 49 percent fall of gold imports in
August compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Middle East countries produce 514,000 cars a year,
accounting for 0.9 percent of the world's total production,
Egypt's Alam Al Yom reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Asia and the Pacific region are the biggest car production
centers, which supply 33 percent of the world's total, followed by
North America with an output of 28.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has reached a deal with the United States to buy
890,000 tonnes of wheat, accounting for 20 percent of the total
imports this year, Egypt's Al Akhbar daily said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the wheat price stands at 101 U.S. dollars per
tonne, 25 to 30 percent lower than last year.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Kuwait is expected to earn 1.9 billion dinars (6.27
billion dollars) from oil export in the 1998-99 fiscal year, less
than half the figure of last year due to price slumps, the Al
Hayat newspaper said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Kuwaiti economist Jassim Saadoun as saying
that the Gulf sheikdom will not resort to loans to cover the
ensuing budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
Saadoun said the Kuwaiti government has announced a 20 percent
cut in expenditure in the current fiscal year, but nothing has so
far been done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
