<HEADLINE> Information Industry Pushing Research Institutes To Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China's information industry
wants to shake up its research and development institutes to make
them more market oriented.
</P>
<P>
The new Ministry of the Information Industry (MII) has taken
over more than 70 research and development institutes that used to
belong to the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications and
Ministry of the Electronics Industry.
</P>
<P>
According to MII sources, the ministry will reshuffle these
government-financed institutes in the near future to transform
most of them into financially independent enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Huan, president of the China Academy of Telecommunications
Technology, says that over the next few years, the academy will
develop a hi-tech enterprise group.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years, it has increased its output value from
190 million yuan to 2 billion yuan. Its Datang Telecom Technology
Co. Ltd. attracted a record number of buyers for a single stock
when it was listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange in August.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the academy has already transferred 40 percent
of its staff members to Datang and that it is working on new
technology that will meet the needs of China's telecommunications
market.
</P>
<P>
An official of the former Ministry of Electronics Industry
says that, in the past, research institutes relied on the
government for funding and their main job was projects that the
government assigned, but in recent years, the government has
adopted new policies to encourage them to link research and
development more closely to commercial applications.
</P>
<P>
Now over half of their operating funds come from the
marketplace. Zhou said that the academy wants to get away from
government sponsorship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
