<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda's Strenuous Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, one of the few
countries in the world which suffer most from HIV/AIDS, has
fought a strenuous battle against the pandemic over the past
decade and reaped a lot from its efforts in this aspect.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that a total of more than 500,000 Ugandans
have died of AIDS, ever since the first case was made public in
1982 in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, an estiM;ted one-tenth of its 20 million population
are said to be HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has so far borne the brunt of this scourge, which
constitutes one of the most serious health and socio-economic
problems. It is one of the leading causes of death among adults
and children under five years.
</P>
<P>
According to the HIV/AIDS surveillance report, 53,306
cumulative AIDS cases had been reported and recorded by the end
of 1997. Of these, 49,432 were adults and the rest 3,874 were
almost children below 12 years of age. Owing to under-reporting,
the true figure is projected five to eight times higher.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the rampant spread of AIDS, the overall mean
age of adult AIDS cases was 32.5 years and that of paediatric
AIDS was 2.7 years. It is reported that one million Ugandan
children have been orphaned due to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Babies and children are the innocent victims of this terminal
disease. The infant mortality rate of infants born to
HIV-positive mothers is 163 per 1,000 live births while that for
infants born to non-HIV positive mothers is 34.
</P>
<P>
The HIV-positive children or those born of HIV-positive
mothers face deprivation, stigmatization and discrimination. They
are most likely to drop out of school and most vulnerable to
sexual abuse and harassment.
</P>
<P>
This hindrance to socio-economic development was timely
recognized by the Ugandan government which has taken a series of
effective measures to curb the growth of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The struggle against HIV/AIDS in Uganda can be categorized in
three phases.
</P>
<P>
The first phase was during the early 1980s. Government and
public response to the new disease was initially ad hoc and slow.
In this phase, the communities, especially families and clans,
together with the non-governmental organizations and the
religious sector spontaneously took responsibility of the
response by providing care and support to the infected.
</P>
<P>
It took some four years before the country was officially and
categorically told of the dangers of the epidemic. This means
that action to address the epidemic in a systematic way was
similarly delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda's Strenuous Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The second phase was in the latter half of 1980s. The
Ministry of Health took official charge of coordinating the
national response through the AIDS Control Program.
</P>
<P>
Within four years, the government made strides in
epidemiology, significantly reducing infection through blood
transfusion and laying a solid foundation for Uganda's now quite
effective Information, Education and Communication (IEC)
intervention which has created more than 90 percent of public
awareness about the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The IEC program also attracted international community to
assist Uganda through supporting and supplementing the activities
of the program.
</P>
<P>
From then on started the third phase. In 1990, a National Task
Force on AIDS was set up, which reviews the country's approach
and coordinates nationwide efforts.
</P>
<P>
Major international agencies operating in the country were
actively involved in the exercise, the culmination of which is
the establishment of Uganda AIDS Commission and the formation and
development of the National Multisectoral Strategy.
</P>
<P>
With enhancement of public awareness and establishment of more
clinics across the country, HIV prevalence trends have declined
in urban areas from the highest rate of 30 percent to an average
high of 15 percent. In some rural areas, the rate has plummeted
from 43 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, people have begun to undertake voluntary testing and
counseling. Basic and clinical research has also recorded a
great breakthrough. HIV vaccine and drug development have also
achieved a lot. Uganda was recently chosen as one of the few
pilot countries for AIDS drug trials.
</P>
<P>
These achievements cannot guarantee that the prospect of
curbing this disease in Uganda is bright and rosy. It still has
a long way to go and has many challenges to face. Inadequate
funding, difficulty in ensuring positive behavior change and
sensitization programs are all severe hindrances to further
achievement.
</P>
<P>
However, as President Yoweri Museveni said at an AIDS
conference Monday morning, Uganda, together with many other
sub-Sahara countries which suffer from this disease, will
continue its battle against AIDS, the leading cause of death for
young Africans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
