<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls Victim to Quiet Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar edged
lower Tuesday, continuing this week's trend of quiet, range-bound
local trade.
</P>
<P>
The local unit ended a little weaker at 58.43 U.S. cents from
58.67 here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank foreign exchange dealer Will Richardson said the
week had been very quiet for the Australian dollar with the focus
on offshore events.
</P>
<P>
He said the local currency was failing to make an impact during
trading in sessions.
</P>
<P>
The currency spent the session in a range of 58.30 U.S. cents
to 58.50.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the fact that the Australian dollar had failed
to break through on the topside a couple of times on the day
indicated the risks for the currency were on the downside.
</P>
<P>
"It is really dependent on the U.S. dollar," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
"If the Japanese come out with an agreement on the banking
reform package and the U.S. dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate goes
to 130 yen then Aussie will reach 60.00 U.S cents again."
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney, the local currency was trading at 78.69
Japanese yen from 78.10 and 0.9889 German marks from 0.9880
previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
