<HEADLINE> South Korea, Japan to Enter Crucial Fishery Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan will
begin critical rounds of talks on a new fishery pact in Tokyo
Wednesday, the Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Japan Tuesday, Yun Byung-se, deputy director
general of the ministry's Asian and Pacific Affairs Bureau, said
South Korea and Japan could narrow their differences on most
contentious issues to work out a draft fishery accord which will
replace the 1965 fishing accord.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that South Korean Minister of Maritime Affairs
and Fisheries Kim Sun-kil is scheduled to meet with his Japanese
counterpart Shoichi Nakagawa Wednesday for the joint-fishing area
issue. The ministry used to say that the issue of where to
establish a joint fishing area should be decided at
ministerial-level negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few months, South Korea and Japan have been
working for for an early settlement of the fishery issues as they
set October 7 this year when President Kim Dae-jung pays a state
visit to Japan as the deadline for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
In the past talks, South Korea and Japan have been at odds on
where to set up the new joint fishing area in waters between them.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which has tried to keep Korean fishing vessels away from
its coast rich in maritime resources, reportedly insists that the
joint fishing area does not extend beyond the longitude of 135
degrees east while South Korea demands the area be extended as far
as the longitude of 136 degrees east.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1965 fisheries pact, South Korean and Japanese
fishing boats are allowed to operate in all waters, except for the
12-mile exclusive fishing zones off each other's coasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
