<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Lose $80M to Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria may lose 71 billion
Naira (about 80 million U.S. Dollars) in export earnings this
year due to the lingering Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Tuesday quoted a report by the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) as saying
that the loss from the Asian crisis may lower Nigeria's gross
domestic product (GDP) by 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD report titled "Trade Implications of the East Asian
Crisis: Impact on Markets for Primary Commodities," identifies
Nigeria, Algeria, Angola, Cameroun, Gabon, Egypt and other
African countries as vulnerable to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's fate is indicative of the experience of developing
countries that are largely dependent on export of primary
commodities, such as gold, wood, oil, cotton, sugar, palm oil,
cocoa and coffee.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Asian countries are not only
importing fewer commodities, but also producing at cheaper costs
and dumping more products on African countries.
</P>
<P>
There has also been a general fall in prices of primary
products, due to depressed demand. For example, petroleum prices
have declined sharply and the impact on petroleum exporting
countries is particularly strong, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the report said, Asian crisis will lead to less
investment from Asia and reduce the competitivity of African
products, therefore, threatening Africa's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
However, it is not bad news for Africa, the newspaper said,
adding that machinery made in Asia for processing farm products
will become cheaper and this is an advantage of the crisis for
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper called for the establishment of an African-Asian
forum to explore possible opportunities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
