<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Fire Destroys S. Somali District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fire has devastated
the southern Somalia's Sablale district, 235 km south of the
capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to reports received through the VHF radios, Monday's
fire has destroyed more than 80 percent of the town's residential
areas, leaving behind only 30 houses out of the nearly 1,500
ones.
</P>
<P>
The fire has also destroyed all of the main food stores, shops
and the market of the town. The people of Sablale have just
returned to the town after seven months of exodus to the nearby
villages following heavy floods that besieged the town from every
corner during the disastrous floods early in the year, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire is not known. However, people from the
town attributed the fire that gushed into their houses to the
wildly grown grass that caught fire and took over all of the
residential areas. The grass had grown to more than a meter high
during the absence of the people after the floods.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi Ali Rage, the district commissioner, said the
population of the town has moved to the nearby village of Muddul
Barawe, 30 west of Sablale for safety.
</P>
<P>
Despite the great misfortune, there has been no reports of
casualties caused by the fire other than a man called Mukhtar Ali
Unka who remained missing since the fire started.
</P>
<P>
"We believe he is dead by now lying under the rubble of the
fire," said the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi Ali Rage noted that the town now remains to have the
same name but without its numerous houses.
</P>
<P>
"Now we can say it drew to the size of a small village rather
than a district," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moallim Biyana, an owner of a small house in Sablale, said he
has moved his family to Muddul Barawe village now, but without
any food. He said he has been trying to recover from the last
year's floods. "Neither floods nor fire leave anything for the
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The district commissioner had appealed to the world community
and the international non-governmental organizations to give a
helping hand especially to the women and children who just fled
without any food, shelter or medicine.
</P>
<P>
"The water would let the people at least to take with them
some of their food and clothes, but the fire does not give any
chance," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
