<HEADLINE> Indian Union Cabinet Recommends Imposing President's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP)-led Union Cabinet in an over-two-hour meeting here Tuesday
decided to recommend to the president to dismiss the present Rabri
Devi government in eastern India's Bihar state and impose
president's rule over it.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet also recommended keeping the State Assembly in
suspended animation.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet after a long discussion accepted the report by
State Governor Sundar Singh Bhandari who had recommended
imposition of president's rule in the state.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation for dismissal of the Bihar state government
came a day after the Rabri government won a vote of confidence in
the State Assembly.
</P>
<P>
When asked why the Union Cabinet made the recommendation, Union
Home Minister L. K. Advani said, "It was not just the law and
order situation. The state seems to have withered away in Bihar."
</P>
<P>
The present Bihar government, which is ruled by an opposition
party, Tuesday called a state-wide strike Wednesday in protest
against the center's recommendation to impose president's rule in
the state. The decision was taken after the state cabinet held an
emergency meeting to review the situation arising out of the Union
Cabinet's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
State ministers said the strike was called to protest against
the discriminatory, unconstitutional and draconian action of the
Union Cabinet. It is a murder of democracy and politically
motivated move.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties such as Congress and Communist Party of
India, are opposed to the imposition of president's rule in Bihar.
Even some of BJP partners have also shared oppositions' view over
the issue. Some opposition parties even said that the law and
order situation in the BJP- ruled Uttar Pradesh and Maharashtra
states is worse than Bihar, and president's rule should have been
first imposed in these two states.
</P>
<P>
Union Law Minister M. Thambidurai, who comes from one of BJP's
partners, demanded the dismissal of the Tamil Nadu government of
southern India when the Union Cabinet Tuesday took up the issue of
imposition of president's rule in Bihar.
</P>
<P>
The president is reportedly to have told the BJP government
delegation which called on him here Tuesday that he would go
through the governor's report and consult other opposition parties
before taking a decision on the cabinet recommendation.
</P>
<P>
More political unrest is expected to follow in the country if
president's rule is imposed on Bihar, one of the biggest and
poorest states in India, diplomatic circles here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
