<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smog Choking Congested Streets in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Worsening air pollution
has continued to ravage traffic-congested, skyscraper-packed urban
areas in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Protection Department (EPD) Tuesday recorded
"very high" air pollution index of 167 on the roadside in Causeway
Bay, a bustling business district on the Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The figure indicated deteriorating roadside air quality from
that of Monday and Sunday, when the pollution index was measured
between 135 and 138.
</P>
<P>
Pang Sik-wing, Principal Environment Protection Officer, blamed
a high level of nitrogen dioxide for the poor roadside air
quality.
</P>
<P>
"The moderate northerly wind has brought a background ozone
level to Hong Kong. The ozone enhanced the oxidation of nitric
oxide emitted from diesel vehicles into nitrogen dioxide, which
could not disperse quickly among high-rise buildings," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
About two thirds of vehicles in Hong Kong still use diesel, the
main local air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
The general air pollution index sampled in different parts of
Hong Kong was also "high", ranging between 74 and 86, according to
EPD. Visibility was poor despite the sunny weather because of
photochemical reactions. The department advised people with heart
and respiratory illnesses to stay indoors.
</P>
<P>
The air pollution is likely to stay for a few days as similar
weather conditions will last for some time, according to the
officer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
