<HEADLINE> Thai Tourism Head Leaves for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Jurin Laksanawisit, chairman
of the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT), left for China Tuesday
at the head of an 18-strong delegation to build travel and
sporting relations with a country that is rapidly becoming one of
Thailand's major tourist source-markets, a TAT press release said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his week-long visit, Jurin will meet with senior
officials of the China National Tourism Administration and lead a
series of table-top shows between Thai sellers and Chinese buyers
in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou from September 22 to 28.
</P>
<P>
The TAT is focusing on China as one of its top markets for
1998/99. Jurin will be informing the Chinese travel trade of a
number of measures taken by the two governments to remove barriers
to travel, such as offering visa on arrival facilities.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people from the southwestern province of Yunnan can now
visit up to nine provinces in northern Thailand with only a
special entry document to obtain visa-on-arrival at border
checkpoints in promoting Greater Mekong Sub-region and
intra-regional travel.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 54 direct flights a week linking China
with Thailand by Thai Airways International and five Chinese
airlines.
</P>
<P>
This means there is no shortage of seat capacity which will
provide a strong foundation for continued growth in visitors from
China to Thailand, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, China was Thailand's sixth largest market overall and
for the first six months of this year, it is ranked as the third
largest market in Asia. Since 1992, visitor arrivals from China
have more than tripled and are continuing this healthy trend, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
Jurin, as minister in charge of sports, will also seek to
generate interest among the Chinese sports community to send an
extra-large delegation to participate in the 13th Asian Games to
be held in Bangkok between December 6 and 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
