<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Commodity Export Incomes Expected to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian commodity export
earnings for the financial year of 1998-1999 would be slightly
lower than the previous year, Australia's official chief commodity
forecaster said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Total commodity export receipts were expected to reach 66.5
billion Australian dollars (38.57 billion U.S. dollars) in
1998-1999, down 530 million Australian dollars (307 million U.S.
dollars), or 0.8 percent, from the previous year's tally, the
Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics (ABARE)
said in its latest snapshot of the nation's commodity outlook.
</P>
<P>
However, higher farm production spurred on by rain and the
prospect of even more competitive exports from a further drop in
the Australian dollar make the latest predictions almost 2 billion
Australian dollars (1.16 billion U.S. dollars) more optimistic
than ABARE's previous quarterly estimate of 64.5 billion
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report reveals a mixed bag in which some commodities are
faring better than others amidst the worsening world economy and
warns the Asian crisis could still deepen.
</P>
<P>
The mineral resources sector, where export earnings are tipped
to rise 1.5 percent to 41.9 billion Australian dollars (24.3
billion U.S. dollars), remains a strong performer.
</P>
<P>
"Although world prices of most minerals are forecast to be flat
or down, an assumed 15 percent fall in the Australian dollar means
that prices received by local exporters will be higher," ABARE
Executive Director Brian Fisher said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Dairy exports are expected to surge past 2 billion Australian
dollars, thanks to a lower Australian dollar expected to average
58 U.S. cents over 1998-1999, and the outlook for cotton and beef
is also brighter.
</P>
<P>
Australia's farm sector overall is expected to contribute about
22 billion Australian dollars (12.76 billion U.S. dollars) to
total export revenue, down four percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Large world stocks and increasing competition should offset the
benefits of a lower Australian dollar for wheat growers, leading
to a drop of 25 Australian dollars in wheat production profit to
170 Australian dollars per ton over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau slashed its eastern market wool indicator forecast
to an average 560 Australian cents a kilogram clean from its
previous estimate of 655 Australian cents, citing weak demand and
strong competition from cheaper, synthetic fibers.
</P>
<P>
Fisher said the stability of the Chinese currency is important
for Australian commodity producers as China is one of the leading
customers of some Australian commodities, such as iron ore and
wool.
</P>
<P>
He explained that a weaker Chinese currency could hit
Australia's exports of wool, cotton and some minerals by making
them more expensive for China to import as well as indirectly
hurting Australian exporters through lower world prices.
</P>
<P>
China has pledged time and again that it would not devalue its
currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Detained for Involvement in Rioting in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 17 foreign
nationals were among 132 people detained here during the past two
days for involvement in illegal assembly and rioting in Malaysia,
police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners detained were nine Indonesians, two Pakistanis,
an Afghan and five others whose nationality had yet to be
ascertained, Ghazali Mohd Amin, superintendent of public relations
of the federal police headquarters here, said in a statement
issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Police released 107 of them on bail after questioning while 25
others were still being detained, he said.
</P>
<P>
All of them were detained Monday and early Tuesday for taking
part in illegal assemblies or rioting by supporters of former
Malaysian deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim in front of the
courthouse here and the National Stadium in Bukit Jalil near here.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was sacked as deputy prime minister and finance minister
on September 2 and a day later was expelled from the ruling United
Malays National Organization (UMNO) of which he was deputy
president for "low morals." He was arrested by police at his house
here on Sunday night after leading an alleged illegal rally and
procession which later erupted into rioting. Police used water
cannon and fired tear gas to disperse the crowd.
</P>
<P>
In Ghazali's statement, the public are advised not to join and
to stay away from illegal assemblies organized by "irresponsible
elements."
</P>
<P>
Ghazali said public cooperation would greatly help the police
maintain law and order and ease traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the federal capital is quite normal Tuesday.
</P>
