<HEADLINE> China Reducing Amount Of Logging In Lesser Hinggan Mountains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Yichun City in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province has started protecting forest
resources by reducing timber cutting in a forest farm in the
Lesser Hinggan Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The four-million-hectare Yichun forest farm has a forest
coverage of 72 percent and is a major production base of Korean
pines. Forest resources and timber reserves there have been
shrinking rapidly in the past years because of excessive cutting.
</P>
<P>
The forest farm will cut timber production by 30 percent in the
next 2 years, with the annual timber output being cut from 2.26
million cubic meters to 1.59 million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the forest farm's 16 organizations will completely stop
logging and shift to growing trees and doing other business and
the remaining 6 will limit timber production.
</P>
<P>
The farm will close 500,000 hectares of mountainous areas for
afforestation and authorities have changed cutting operations,
banning the use of machines in logging zones to protect the growth
of young trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Gas Reserve 10th Largest in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's natural gas reserve
stood at 124 trillion standard cubic feet, or 3.4 trillion
standard cubic meters as at the end of 1997, which is the 10th
largest in the world, the Nigerian Tribune said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Dalhatu Bayero, managing director of the
Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) as making the
disclosure at a seminar entitled "Nigerian gas, from waste to
resources" in capital Abuja Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official also put Nigeria's crude oil reserve at 25
billion barrels, with a production ratio of about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Bayero said the country's gas reserve may increase to 300
trillion standard cubic feet or 8.41 trillion standard cubic
meters as exploration continues.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the NNPC have put in place 1,800 kilometers
of gas pipeline network with a daily designed delivery capacity
of 2.5 billion standard cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
Through the pipelines, natural gas are currently delivered to
Lagos, Kogi and Akwa Ibom states from gas fields in the Niger
Delta basin, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, regretted that the absence of a
national gas policy, inadequate pricing and shortage of fund are
preventing Nigeria from a better utilization of its gas
resources.
</P>
<P>
According to him, about 80 percent of the gas produced in
association with crude oil are currently being flared in Nigeria,
compared with less than 20 percent in other major oil-producing
countries such as Saudi Arabia, Libya, Iran and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The official called for a deregulation of the energy market to
encourage private investment and a national gas policy to define
the roles of producers, end-users and the government.
</P>
<P>
In this end, he disclosed that the government has already
approved the construction of a 350 megawatts power plant in the
Rivers State by the Mobile Production Nigeria Corporation, which
will be powered by natural gas produced by Mobile and NNPC's oil
fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
