<HEADLINE> Zambia's Horticultural Sector to Reap $52M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is expected to reap
about 104 billion Kwacha or 52 million U.S. Dollars from its
horticultural sector this season.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Tuesday quoted Mable Mandela, chief
executive of Zambia Export Growers Association (ZEGA) who made
the projection, as saying that the country's horticultural sector
was expected to expand by an estimated one third over last
season's earnings of 40 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Volume of exports over the 1997/98 export season were 5,500
tons which earned us about 40 million U.S. Dollars, recording a
35 percent increase on the previous year," Mandela said in an
interview at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
She added that the volume is expected to rise further as
hectarage has been expanded to over 30 percent for the current
1998/99 export season.
</P>
<P>
The horticultural sector ranks as one of the major foreign
exchange earners in Zambia and is also generating a lot of
employment in the country, with over 8,000 people employed in the
sector, according to Mandela.
</P>
<P>
She noted that more and more indigenous people including women
are entering the sector, most of whom are taking advantage of
ZEGA's open door policy especially in the area of providing
information pertaining to the industry, which is rated the third
biggest exporter in Africa, after Kenya and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
