<HEADLINE> Nigeria Stock Exchange Suspends 32 Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Stock Exchange
(NSE) has suspended trading in shares of 32 companies who has
failed to pay their listing fee, according to media reports
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the suspension order was passed to the securities
dealers at Monday's trading session, at the end of a three-week
ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
About 70 companies were warned three weeks ago to pay their
listing fee or face sanctions, while the 32 suspended firms have
apparently failed to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Among the suspended is the Nigeria Cement Company Plc, which
is the oldest quoted company at the NSC, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that the suspension may lead to the de-listing
of some of the 32 firms who have been dormant and non performing
for some time.
</P>
<P>
Up to the first half of 1997, there were 183 listed firms at
the NSE, with a total capitalization of about 4.6 billion U.S.
Dollars. 
</P>
