<HEADLINE> More S. African Soldiers Wounded in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 11 South
African soldiers were wounded since South African troops crossed
into Lesotho Tuesday morning to help restore stability in the
mountain kingdom, the South African National Defense Force said.
</P>
<P>
Six of those injured were taken to hospitals in South Africa,
and others did not need hospitalization and were remaining in
Lesotho, South African National Defense Force (SANDF) spokesman
Louis Kirstein said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
None of the soldiers was seriously injured. Some were hit by
shrapnel, while others suffered light wounds, Kirstein said.
</P>
<P>
Laverne Machine, another SANDF spokeswoman, said contrary to
earlier reports, 200 troops from Botswana had not yet arrived in
Lesotho, but were expected to join the 600 South African soldiers
soon.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said earlier that the Botswana peace-keeping
troops, escorted by South African police, were on their way to
Maseru, the capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
South African armored personnel carriers, attack helicopters
and mortar units have been involved in peace-keeping mission,
Machine said.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports quoted military spokesman Ben van Zyl as
saying that rebel Lesotho soldiers were at 10.30 a.m. still
shooting at South African peace-keeping troops.
</P>
<P>
"There are skirmishes taking place at military bases outside
Maseru, with rebel Lesotho soldiers shooting at our people."
However, Van Zyl said, the center of Maseru had largely been
stabilized.
</P>
<P>
He said some looting broke out in some places, but the
peace-keeping troops had brought the situation under control.
</P>
<P>
He said it was difficult to tell how long it would take to
restore stability in Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Adri Cronje, spokeswoman for the South African Foreign Affairs
Department said in Pretoria that government buildings, including
Royal Palace and the High court in Maseru had apparently been set
alight.
</P>
<P>
In addition, shops in the city were looted and vehicles with
South African registration plates were stoned.
Cronje said no more information was immediately available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
