<HEADLINE> S. Korea's LG Develops 50-Inch Plasma Display Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean LG Electronics
announced Tuesday that it has developed a new 50-inch plasma
display panel (PDP) television.
</P>
<P>
The 50-inch thin but high-resolution screen is as large as four
25-inch wide-screen TV sets put together. Users can even put the
TV on the wall and turn their living room into a theater.
</P>
<P>
The new TV is fit for digital TV broadcasting and can also
handle computer signals and users can connect their audio, video
and digital versatile disk players directly to the new TV system,
said the company.
</P>
<P>
The LG PDP system is based on new technology allowing it to cut
production costs by 30 percent. It will display the new system at
Asia Display'98' exhibition scheduled for September 28 in Seoul,
said a LG spokesman.
</P>
<P>
It is the first South Korean TV manufacturer to develop such a
large PDP TV. Globally, a few Japanese companies, including NEC
and Pioneer, are spearheading the new technology, according to the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The global market for the PDP systems is expected to reach 2.5
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000 and 10 billion dollars by
2005.
</P>
<P>
LG plans to invest 900 billion won (some 700 million dollars)
by 2005 to build a plant with annual production capacity of 1.2
million units in bid to to grab 12 percent of the global market.
</P>
</TEXT>
