<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African and
Botswanan troops have taken over two Lesotho Defense Force bases
since entering the mountain kingdom early Tuesday morning on
peace-keeping mission, the South African National Defense Force
(SANDF) said.
</P>
<P>
The peace-keeping soldiers had also secured Katse Dam Project
in Lesotho to protect civilians including South Africans working
at the site, said Lieutenant-Colonel Laverne Machine, head of
SANDF joint operations, in Pretoria, the administrative capital
of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
She said the two military bases secured were near Maseru,
capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
However, she could not confirm that at least one peace-keeping
soldier was wounded and a South African television cameraman
injured, saying that casualty figures were still being awaited.
</P>
<P>
For now, the Royal Palace of Lesotho King Letsie III in Maseru
is under protection, Machine said.
</P>
<P>
The military intervention follows unsuccessful attempts by a
Southern African Development Community (SADC) team to mediate a
negotiated settlement to a crisis sparked by opposition claims
that Lesoth's May 23 election was rigged. 
</P>
