<HEADLINE> S. African Troops Storm Lesotho Royal Palace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- South African troops
moved into Lesotho early Tuesday morning and stormed the royal
palace in Maseru, where about 800 opposition supporters are said
to have taken refuge, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Youths were throwing stones at members of the task force and
are damaging vehicles with South African registration plates.
Sporadic gunfire has been heard from inside and outside the
palace grounds, South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Heavy gunfire was also heard at the Makoanyane barracks east
of Maseru just before 6:00 a.m. (0400 GMT) Tuesday morning, the
SABC said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that at least three South African soldiers have
been killed and about 11 wounded in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Mamello Morrison, spokeswoman for the Lesotho opposition
alliance, condemned the intervention.
</P>
<P>
"President N. Mandela, the president of South Africa, has sent
troops of soldiers to come and butcher innocent Lesotho (people)
who are fighting for their democratic rights," she said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
According to South African Press Association (SAPA), about 600
South African soldiers crossed the border at about 5:00 a.m.
(0300 GMT) to help restore order in the tiny mountain kingdom.
About 200 Botswanan troops are on their way to Maseru, said SAPA.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force spokesperson Laverne
Machine said the troops would withdraw as soon as the mission had
been completed.
</P>
<P>
She said the military intervention was being undertaken at the
request of the Lesotho government, under the auspices of the
Southern African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
Opposition supporters, who camped outside the royal palace
since early August, have paralyzed the government by blocking
civil servants from going to work and hijacking government
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They are protesting against the results of the May 23 general
elections, which they claim were rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The intervention followed fruitless efforts by South African
mediators over the weekend to bring the government and opponents
together in talks after the release of a three-nation commission
report looking into opposition allegations of electoral fraud.
</P>
<P>
The report compiled by legal experts from South Africa,
Botswana and Zimbabwe said there were irregularities in the May
election, but failed to say for sure whether it was rigged.
</P>
</TEXT>
