<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Explains Why His Former Deputy Was Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday police were forced to detain his
former deputy Anwar Ibrahim under the Internal Security Act (ISA)
when he instigated violence.
</P>
<P>
Despite his detention under the ISA, Anwar would still be
charged in court when police had enough evidence, Mahathir told a
news conference at his office here Tuesday afternoon where he
explained why Anwar was detained.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was sacked as deputy prime minister and finance
minister on September 2 and the following day was expelled from
the ruling United Malays National Organization (UMNO) of which he
was the deputy president for "low morals", was arrested by police
at his house here Sunday night after leading an alleged illegal
rally and procession which later erupted into rioting.
</P>
<P>
It was not the intention of the police to arrest Anwar under
the ISA, Mahathir who is also home minister said, adding police
had intended to arrest and charge Anwar Ibrahim in court.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said police arrested Anwar under the ISA due to his
violent behavior, believing it is their intention to charge Anwar
"in the right manner".
</P>
<P>
Anwar was alleged to be involved in several sexual offenses and
was implicated in other charges.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Anwar delivered an inflammatory speech at an
"illegal" gathering at Masjid Negara (National Mosque) here,
instigating his supporters to riot.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he had not expected Anwar to go that extent. Even
the police did not believe that there would be violence and had
been preparing to make an ordinary arrest with proper charges, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The police had to act," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 132 people, including 17 foreigners, were detained
here during the past two days for involvement in illegal assembly
and rioting by supporters of the former deputy prime minister,
according to police Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said at the press conference the situation in the
country is "very much stable and there is no need for anybody to
worry".
</P>
<P>
He denied that the government was planning to declare a state
of emergency, saying "There is no need for it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists: Potassium, Magnesium Lower Stroke Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Food rich in potassium
and magnesium may help reduce the risk of stroke especially in
people with high blood pressure, a study said.
</P>
<P>
The study, published Tuesday in Circulation, a journal of the
American Heart Association, was conducted by a group of scientists
of Harvard School of Public Health between 1986 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Ascherio, leading author of the study, said he and his
colleagues looked at 43,738 men aged 40-75 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Over the next eight years, more than 300 of those men had
strokes, and those with the highest potassium consumption were 38
percent less likely to have a stroke than those with the lowest
intake.
</P>
<P>
He also said that men with the highest intake of magnesium (452
milligrams per day) had 30 percent lower stroke risk than those
who consumed the lowest level (243 milligrams per day).
</P>
<P>
Both potassium and magnesium are found in high concentrations
in fruit and vegetables, such as bananas, tomatoes, spinach and
oranges.
</P>
<P>
A big potassium intake means a lot of vegetables by American
standard -- about nine servings of fruits and vegetables a day,
compared with four a day in the group that ate the least.
</P>
<P>
Though those who were taking potassium supplements had a 60
percent lower risk of stroke compared to men with high blood
pressure who were not taking the supplements, Ascherio warned,
potassium supplements should not be taken without a doctor's
supervision because high levels can be harmful especially for
people with kidney problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar to Average 58 US Cents in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia's official chief
commodity forecaster Tuesday further downgraded its forecast for
the Australian dollar and said that the nation's export earnings
would drop slightly in the 1998-1999 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics'
(ABARE) latest quarterly commodity report forecast an average
level for the dollar of about 58 U.S. cents over the financial
year of 1998-1999, down six cents from its previous estimate of 64
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar depreciated markedly during mid-July and
late August, plunging to a record low of 55.95 U.S. cents on
August 27, due to concerns about the deteriorating outlook for
Asia and instability in emerging markets including Russia and
South America.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended its trading on the local market at
58 U.S. cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 58 U.S. cent level was about 15 percent lower than the
average of 68 U.S. cents in the financial year of 1997-1998 and 26
percent less than the 1996-1997 average of 78 U.S. cents, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Australian dollar has helped offset the
impact of low commodity prices in the world market on Australian
commodity exporters, as most of the commodities are set in U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yet a weaker Russian currency is expected to make Russian
commodities more competitive than the Australian ones, taking away
part of Australia's share of world market.
</P>
<P>
Short-term export performance is expected to be weak and export
earnings forecast is to drop 0.8 percent to 66.5 billion
Australian dollars (38.57 billion U.S. dollars) in the 1998-1999
financial year, which ends on June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"But domestic demand, especially private consumption
expenditure, is assumed to remain firm," the report said.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said the nation's economic growth is assumed to average
at 2.75 percent in 1998-1999, the same as the government's revised
official forecast released earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
World economic growth is expected to fall from 4.1 percent in
1997 to 2.1 percent this year, and although economic activity in
some East and Southeast Asian countries should stabilize next
year, the situation remains volatile and there is a significant
probability that the conditions could worsen, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
