<HEADLINE> Johannesburg Houses Among World's Cheapest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Premium residential
property in the South African metropolis of Johannesburg is
ranked among the cheapest in the world, according to a survey by
an international property consultant company.
</P>
<P>
In its "Lifestyles Around the World" survey report, Knight
Frank International said prices of up-market property in
Johannesburg, the biggest commercial center in southern Africa,
had fallen about 10 percent over the past year, Business Day
paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons are the prospect of political uncertainty
after South African President Nelson Mandela retires next year
and the high level of crimes in the city.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which examined not only the costs of buying and
renting homes but also the essential "must haves" for high-flying
executives, found prices to be about 130,000 U.S. Dollars in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
It also found that while city residents worldwide preferred
diverse international holiday destinations, South Africans chose
to head for internal destinations such as Cape Town and game
reserves.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the Lackluster property market in Johannesburg,
prices of houses in London had continued to rise by between 10
percent and 15 percent over the past year.
</P>
<P>
London, Hong Kong and New York were the most expensive cities
in which to live, with a spacious apartment in New York's Upper
West Side costing about 2.5 million Dollars, up 30 percent on a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Freehold houses in London, ranging between 800,000 and 2.5
million Dollars, were in short supply.
</P>
<P>
Despite prices falling by about 35 percent in the past year,
Hong Kong remained one of the world's most expensive cities, with
an apartment on the south side of the city costing upwards of 2.2
million Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
