<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Promises to Hand Out Any Secret Money If Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto will produce a letter authorizing the Attorney General's
Office to withdraw money from his secret bank accounts if it finds
evidence of their existence, Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Soeharto said anybody who finds these bank accounts, here or
abroad, or has any information about them, should report to the
Attorney General's Office... he is ready to come to the Attorney
General's office any time, if anybody finds these bank accounts
and that he will provide us a letter of authority to withdraw the
money," Ghalib said.
</P>
<P>
He said Soeharto made the statement to him and Coordinating
Minister for Development Supervision Hartarto Sastrosoeharto at
the former president's residence here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto and Ghalib met with Soeharto to clarify the former
president's recent statement that he does not have a single cent
kept in overseas bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
Last week, President B.J. Habibie set up two teams to directly
examine Soeharto over his statement. A team led by Ghalib
comprising the chief of the Indonesian Police and head of the
state audit body, and another team led by Hartarto and Ghalib will
focus on probing Soeharto's alleged overseas wealth.
</P>
<P>
American magazine Forbes estimated in July that Soeharto, who
stepped down amid mounting public pressure on May 21, had a
fortune of 4 billion U.S. dollars. But Soeharto swore that he did
not have any deposits abroad in a statement broadcast by his own
daughter's television station on September 6.
</P>
<P>
"Soeharto reiterated this to us on Monday night," the attorney
general said, adding that the former president expressed his
readiness to be investigated over his alleged wealth hidden in
bank accounts here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
"During the meeting, the former president has shown his
cooperation and he was very helpful," Ghalib said.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto told reporters that Soeharto is ready to give Habibie
a list of his personal wealth acquired until this year.
</P>
<P>
"About his wealth abroad, the former president said he does not
have any savings, company stakes or bonds abroad. He also admitted
that he was never a client of any bank abroad," Hartarto said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time an official probe was launched on
Soeharto, who was in power for 32 years until the country's worst
political and economic crisis in decades forced him to step down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
