<HEADLINE> Military Exercise Begins in Central Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A military exercise began
Tuesday in an area near the Uzebek capital of Tashkent, according
to the Uzebek Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named "Central Asian Peacekeeping Camp-98",
is aimed at coordinating the troops from three central Asian
countries and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in
peace-keeping and humanitarian aid operations.
</P>
<P>
The camp, based in Kazakhstan, was established in May 1996,
with more than 500 servicemen from Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and
Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
Troops from Russia, Azerbaijan and Georgia are also
participating in the four-day exercise, which is expected to end
in a southern town of Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
The exercise is a part of NATO's "Partnership for Peace"
manoeuvres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
