<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today that the fact that
U.S. President Bill Clinton is currently faced with difficulties
will not affect Sino-U.S. relations, "because it is the internal
affair of the United States."
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks at today's regular press conference in
response to a question raised by a reporter on the Sino-US
relations.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, Chinese President Jiang Zemin recently wrote
to Clinton and expressed his belief that the common grounds
reached by the two sides during the exchange of visits by them
will be turned into reality, so as to push Sino-U.S. relations
forward to the goal of establishing constructive strategic
partnership .
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that improving and developing Sino-U.S. relations is
the common desire of the people of China and the United States and
conforms to the fundamental interests of both countries, and is
also the consensus of both the Democratic Party and the Republican
Party of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The successful exchange of visits between the two countries'
presidents has elevated Sino-U.S. relationship to a new stage
of development, Zhu said, adding that China appreciates Clinton's
active contribution to improving Sino-US relations. 
</P>
