<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rallied Tuesday in
Tokyo after a sharp fall with the Nikkei index dropping to its
12-and-a-half-year low on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange advanced 192.51 points, or
1.42 percent, from Monday's close to end at 13,789.81 in a
volatile session of trading.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 2.38 points or 0.23 percent to
1,050.17.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 510
million shares from Monday's 389.85 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders, however, said the gains masked concerns about the poor
health of Japan's economy and the political row surrounding
banking reform.
</P>
<P>
This rebound isn't one you can trust, a dealer said, adding
that the general downward direction would not change.
</P>
<P>
"With the falling economies in Asia and now Latin America,
there is not going to be any more volume growth," another dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
Export-led blue chips withered as domestic corporations sold to
nail down profits before the September-30 end of the fiscal
half-year for most Japanese firms.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,342 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
surpassed losers 594 to 537, with 161 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
