<HEADLINE> 300,000 Mozambicans Need Food Aid: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Joao Zamissa, head of Natural
Disasters Prevention and Combat Department of Mozambique, has
revealed that over 300,000 Mozambicans need food aid from now on
till next April before the new harvest season starts.
</P>
<P>
About 120,000 people are in difficult condition due to drought
or floods. Some have already resorted to wild fruits and plants
for food, he said here Monday, according to Tuesday's Noticias
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Only 22,000 people have so far benefited from the emergency
food aid in Sofala Province in central Mozambique, Cabo Delgado
and Tete provinces in the north, said the official.
</P>
<P>
According to Zamissa, his department has mapped out relief
plans which also include small scale productions in addition to
giving free hand-outs to certain groups of people.
</P>
<P>
On the overall food demand, Zamissa said, a total of 41,600
tons of maize and 3,700 tons of beans are needed between
September this year and April of 1999. Moreover, 818 tons of
rice seeds, 978 tons of bean seeds, 2,000 tons of maize seeds and
789 tons of peanut seeds are also in demand, among others.
</P>
</TEXT>
