<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Earthquake-Proof Historic Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A team of engineers is
using computer software and innovative structural concepts to
earthquake-proof historic buildings in Wellington, the Evening
Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper said that priority has been
given to Parliament buildings, the General Assembly Library and
the old Bank of New Zealand buildings.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand engineers have developed software to simulate how
the buildings would react in an earthquake. From this analysis,
they can pinpoint and strengthen areas of weakness, instead of
strengthening the entire building.
</P>
<P>
It saves cost and also means the building's original character
can be preserved without the need for obtrusive structural work.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the recent refurbishment of Parliament buildings
 included placing more than 400 rubber blocks (base isolation
bearings) in the foundations.
</P>
<P>
The blocks allow lateral movement of up to 35 centimeters in an
earthquake, it added.
</P>
<P>
Other refurbishment and strengthening projects in Wellington
include the former Harbor Board building and the old Maritime
Museum.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, New Zealand education officials
and experts were busy inspecting schools in the capital city to
see whether the safety and welfare of staff and students are
effectively implemented, an evacuation plan is in place and
emergency drills are held regularly.
</P>
<P>
Recently, New Zealand and foreign seismologists have repeatedly
 predicted the inevitability of a huge earthquake of 8 magnitude
on the Richter Scale in the Wellington region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Region Enjoys Warm Weather, More Rainfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- It is a common belief that
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which has
two-thirds of China's total desert area, is very dry and lacks
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
However, local meteorologists have pointed out that Xinjiang is
turning warmer and has been having more rainfall in past
decade.
</P>
<P>
Senior engineer Yang Qing of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Regional Meteorological Center drew this conclusion based on his
analysis of climatic changes during the 1987-1996 period compared
with climatic conditions during the 1967-1986 period.
</P>
<P>
The comparison showed that the annual average temperature in
the areas to the north of the Tianshan Mountains went up by one
degree Celsius in the last decade and 0.3 degrees over the
previous two decades. For the areas to the south of the Tianshan
Mountains, the annual average temperature increased by 0.6 degrees
and 0.2 degrees over the same periods.
</P>
<P>
Yang Qing pointed out that the changes mainly occurred during the
winter months.
</P>
<P>
A statistical analysis also showed that the annual average
rainfall in the last ten years grew by nearly 30 millimeters, or
18 percent, over the decade from 1977 to 1986 in the areas to the
north of the Tianshan Mountains; for areas to the south of the
mountain, the figure rose by 21.9 mm, or 30.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists found that rainfall has increased in the region
for all seasons of the year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jiabao of Xinjiang's meteorological association said that
remote-sensing by meteorological satellites found that the
Taklimakan Desert, called the "sea of death," also is experiencing
rainy seasons. The annual rainfall in the desert now stands at 40
to 60 mm.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the warmer weather and increasing rainfall is
bringing more good than bad, and cited expansion of cotton
planting in the region as an example. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Ruling, Opposition Parties Neck And Neck in Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The National Party, the
ruling
party in New Zealand, has gained two points to draw level with its
major
rival the Labor Party in the latest One Network News-Colmar
Brunton
opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll was the first since last month's collapse of the
coalition
government formed by the National Party and New Zealand First, the
New
Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,000 people polled, 41 percent said they would vote for
the
National Party, an improvement of two points on last month's poll.
</P>
<P>
This shows support for the performance of the current National
Party-
led minority government rising after New Zealand First leader
Winston
Peters was sacked from the government.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party also gained one point more to record 42 percent
of
support.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance was supported by 7 percent, down two percentage
points
from 9 percent in the previous poll. ACT New Zealand remained
unchanged,
registering a support rate of 6 percent, while New Zealand First
lost a
point to record two percent.
</P>
<P>
If translated to a general election, the results would give the
 Labor
Party and the Alliance almost enough seats to form a government.
</P>
<P>
Asked if they would have voted in favor of the government
continuing
in office, as did 62 of the Parliament's 120 members earlier this
month,
42 percent of those polled said that they would and 50 percent
said they
would not.
</P>
<P>
National Party leader Jenny Shipley was the preferred prime
minister
of 28 percent of those polled, five percentage points more than
Labor
Party leader Helen Clark.
</P>
<P>
The poll has an estimated margin of error of 3.2 percent, the
NZPA
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
