<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets up Copyright Protection Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China established a national
copyright protection center in Beijing today to consolidate its
great wall holding back the tide of piracy.
</P>
<P>
"This action again demonstrates the Chinese government's
determination to eradicate copyright piracy," Yu Youxian,
director of the State Copyright Administration (SCA), told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The new center will take over some administrative functions of
the SCA to deal with copyright transfer business and provide
convenience for Chinese and foreign copyright holders, according
to Qi Xiangtong, director of the center.
</P>
<P>
When copyright disputes occur, the center will also
engage in legal procedures as a coordinator or arbitrator, Qi
added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there will be cooperation between the center and
state departments in investigating serious cases and punishing
violators.
</P>
<P>
China published its first Copyright Law in 1991 and
subsequently joined the Berne Convention. Since then, the public's
awareness of copyrights has increased and a protection network
established.
</P>
<P>
Yu said the establishment of the center is a result of
the country's progress in curbing piracy.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that 30,000 authors have planned to be registered
at the center to protect their work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
