<HEADLINE> Logging In Southwestern China's Primeval Forests Stopped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Logging in the primeval
forests of southwest China's Sichuan Province has been stopped as
part of the country's first project to protect natural forest
resources.
</P>
<P>
The region is one of the 3 big forest regions in China, but there
are only 4.65 million hectares of forest left after decades of
logging, that has caused serious degradation of the environment.
</P>
<P>
The region has taken the lead in forest protection
projects. All timber processing plants and markets have been
closed and more than 40,000 workers have been put to work in
forest cultivation and protection, with salaries and costs
financed by the central and provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
Teams have been established to enforce the forest-protection
work and roads that were used for logging purposes have been blown
up in the Panzhihua region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
