<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People In Shanghai Suffering From "Rich-Man Diseases" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- More and more people in the
Chinese city of Shanghai are beginning to suffer from diseases
like high blood pressure, coronary heart disease, hyperlipemia,
diabetes, and obesity.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by two hospitals and Fudan University of
100,000 residents in the city showed an incidence of high blood
pressure of 17 percent, which is comparable to the rate of 18
percent in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that an incidence of coronary heart
disease of 6.2 percent, hyperlipemia 1.9 percent, diabetes 2.8
percent and obesity 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Doctors here say that the 5 "rich-man diseases" can easily lead
to cardiovascular diseases that have become the primary killer of
the middle-aged and elderly in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The city's government departments are analyzing the survey
results and preparing a network for preventing the "rich-man
diseases". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
