<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Halting Sales Of Polluting Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Sales of motor vehicles that
are not equipped with electronic fuel injection systems will be
stopped in the Chinese capital as of January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yixin, director of the Beijing Environmental Protection
Bureau, said that all new cars will be required to have emission
controls as well.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau said that exhaust pollution in the city has got
worse in recent years, with the average daily volume of nitrogen
oxide up from 77 micrograms per cubic meter of air in 1986 to 133
micrograms in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some parts of the city have been under the threat of actinic
smoke because of an excessive amount of nitrogen and carbon
monoxide in the air.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that Beijing now has more than 1.3 million motor
vehicles, and that number is increasing by 15 percent annually.
Some of them have been running far beyond their service time and
are responsible for much of the pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will increase the scrapping of old vehicles and enforce
examinations of cars. It will also urge the use of natural gas and
liquefied petroleum gas by buses and taxis.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, at least 60 percent of the commuter buses and
taxis will use clean fuel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
