<HEADLINE> Beijing Improving Communications Automation Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is now building five
projects to improve its communications automation systems,
according to the city's urban administration committee.
</P>
<P>
Committee director Fu Bainan says that an intelligent traffic
control system will be built on Chang'an Avenue and it is expected
to be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The city will build a system to control police patrol vehicles
with satellite positioning to speed up response time.
</P>
<P>
The third project is a state-of-the-art communications command
center integrating televised monitoring, traffic signals control,
traffic information control, traffic telecommunications, and
the '122' police alarm system.
</P>
<P>
The project will be completed by October 1, 1999, at a cost of
59.27 million yuan (7.14 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The other two projects are an automatic monitoring system
of drivers and violations and a computerized traffic control
system to improve the usage of roads.  
