<HEADLINE> Maslyukov Outlines Three Stages for Boosting Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian First Deputy Prime
Minister Yuri Maslyukov has outlined three key decisions to be
taken by the Russian government on improving the situation in the
country, the Itar-Tass news agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the leaders of local industrial enterprises
held in St. Petersburg on Monday, Maslyukov emphasized the need
for boosting industrial production.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia is to go through three stages to reach this
goal.
</P>
<P>
The first stage, he said, is to set up assembly shops and
principal production lines using foreign technologies. At this
stage, railways and the energy sector should be subsidized to
facilitate a recovery of the food industry and research-intensive
sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The second stage is to resolve the problem of non-payments and
optimize the money supply, Maslyukov said, adding that another
goal at this stage would be to find the way back to the
international economic community and join the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed Russian first deputy prime minister also
said that from mid-1999, the government should launch programs for
targeted support of industries and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is time "we summoned up courage and decided
what to do with the defense sector of economy, as we do not need
the volumes of nuclear production, submarines, and aircraft
production we used to have."
</P>
<P>
Maslyukov regarded as the government's priorities making an
industrial policy, and increasing exports and reducing imports.
</P>
</TEXT>
