<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready to Revise Copyright Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- China is ready to revise its
seven-year-old copyright law to bring it in line with
international norms in a real sense, sources revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
Shen Rengan, Deputy Director of the State Copyright
Administration (SCA), told a press conference that the National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, has placed the
revision on its agenda this year.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for revising the law began four years ago,
according to Shen. The SCA handed the draft plan to the State
Council early this year and it is now being debated among
officials and experts across the country.
</P>
<P>
Shen said the NPC and the SCA have held several forums to
discuss this issue, and the draft plan is being revised. The State
Council will submit the revised version to the NPC in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
In the early 20th century, China adopted laws to protect
authors' rights. On June 1, 1991, the country's first copyright
law was officially implemented, signaling that China was beginning
to protect copyrights according to some international criteria.
</P>
<P>
However, piracy become rampant in the mid-1990s, aroused
intensified international and domestic concern, and even brought
the United States and China to the verge of a trade war.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, China has revised some parts of its
law which conflicted with the Berne Convention, according to Shen,
adding that the new version is aimed at meeting the demands of the
market economy as well as higher international standards.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the revision will enable foreign and Chinese
copyright owners' rights to be protected equally, and that some
new problems, such as the protection of Internet copyrights, will
be considered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0223 </DOCNO>
