<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Small Banks to Set up Rescue Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Twenty small and medium
sized banks in Kenya will set up a rescue fund to stop a run by
depositors as a banking crisis in the east African state entered
the third week.
</P>
<P>
With an initial target of 600 million Shillings (some 10
million U.S. Dollars), "the Stabilization Fund will help members
in liquidity problems," the banks' spokesman Magan Chandaria
said.
</P>
<P>
"We will shortly be requesting the World Bank for funding to
help set it up," he was quoted by Tuesday's national press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The banks held a meeting Sunday and launched a program called
"Operation Restore Confidence" to stem rising public panic after
three commercial banks were placed under statutory management
within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya also suspended Monday the Ugandan
branch of Trust Bank which was put under statutory management
last week.
</P>
<P>
Banking experts warned that the collapse of any of the small
banks would have far-reaching negative effects on the overall
economy and called for concerted efforts to save them.
</P>
<P>
However, a survey of most small banks showed that business was
as usual on Monday. Most of the banks said they had not put any
limits on the amount and regularity of withdrawals by depositors.
</P>
<P>
Manu Chandaria, a leading industrialist and former chairman of
the Kenya Association of Manufacturers, said Monday the banks
were seeking the help of Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) to work out
modalities of establishing the fund and that once it is
established, the World Bank would be approached through Treasury
to assist.
</P>
<P>
He said the banks had agreed with CBK's recommendations that
in the long term the small and medium-sized banks should enhance
their capital base or merge to strengthen the local banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
Reliance Bank, Trust Bank and Bullion Bank were placed under
statutory management by the central bank one after another
because they failed to honor checks or meet debt obligations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
