<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt's Cash Demand Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government's need
for money to meet its budget is reducing as demonstrated by the
continued drop in the yield on the popular Treasury Bills (TBs)
and the amount it is seeking from the public.
</P>
<P>
Results of last week's TBs auction show that the yield on the
92-day tenor as well as the 182-day tenor is on a declining trend
for the second week running, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The low yield reduced the amount of money the Central Bank of
Kenya was able to raise from potential investors from 6 billion
to 5.6 billion Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Currently 60.0678 Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The biggest drop was for the 182-day tenor where the yield
dropped from 23 percent the previous week to 22.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The yield on the popular 92-day tenor remained largely at the
previous week's level of 22.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government will be in the market this week seeking a
reduced amount of two billion Shillings compared to 6 billion
Shillings the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Heavy borrowing by the government to meet budgetary needs has
been blamed for the high interest rates prevailing in the banking
sector. Commercial banks use the yield on the bills to set the
base lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
