<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 07:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000-year-old Street Found in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese archaeologists have
found a street with mudbrick houses dating back to 2000 BC
and 2500 BC in northern Lebanon's city of Tripoli, the Daily
Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Consecutive layers of settlements dating from 6000 BC to
1400 AD have been also discovered at Tal Arqa, a 40-meter-high
hill 25 kilometer north of the city.
</P>
<P>
"Underneath the houses (in the street) lay 20 clay pots
which contained the skeletons of children," said archaeologist
Jean Paul Thalmann who heads the excavations.
</P>
<P>
He explained to the paper that in those days people used
to bury their children under the floor of the house.
</P>
<P>
From the structure of the foundations, Thalmann concluded that
the houses were about five meters high and people lived on
the top floor and used the bottom one for storage.
</P>
<P>
Other spectacular finds from the site were a pottery
workshop and a warrior tomb.
</P>
<P>
Excavations at Tal Arqa started in 1972 but were then
delayed by Lebanon's 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Thalmann said so far the excavations have gone through the
mediaeval, Arab, Byzantine, Greek and Phoenician layers and have
now reached the early Bronze age.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of Culture and Higher Education Fawzi
Hobeish had said he would request the United Nations
Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to adopt
Tal Arqa as a world heritage site, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
