<HEADLINE> Liver-Transplant Girl Enrolls in School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An 11-year-old girl who
received a new liver one year ago is now able to go to school with
her new schoolbag just like any other healthy student, it was
reported today in the Beijing Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
Yu Faqin was diagnosed with a liver disease when she was two
years old. In November 1996, doctors from the Xi'an No. 4 Medical
University of the PLA examined her and found early symptoms of
cirrhosis.
</P>
<P>
In June of last year, more than 50 professors, doctors and
nurses took part in an operation which successfully removed the
girl's diseased liver. A new liver was then transplanted,
consisting of one-third of her father's liver.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Morning Post said Yu was the first patient to
undergo and survive a liver transplant in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
