<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Strikes at International Auto Mafia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian authorities busted
three car stealing rings and 38 criminal groups, Chief of the
Central Service for Organized Crime Control Kiril Radev said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 687 stolen cars were found and 20 deluxe cars smuggled
from Canada were confiscated in police operations, Radev said in a
report to an international conference on "Insurance Frauds, Car
Thefts and Smuggling" which opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria will continue to pay attention to the issue of
international car mafia because the country is part of a channel
for transiting and selling cars stolen from West Europe to the
markets of the former Soviet Union and the Middle East, Radev told
the delegates from 20 European countries, the Unites States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Interpol Secretary-General Raymond Kendall, who is also
participating in the conference, praised Bulgaria's Interpol
bureau for its performance.
</P>
<P>
Interpol has more than 1.1 million stolen cars registered as to
September 1, according to Kendall. Most of the cars originated
from Germany, followed by several East European
countries. Bulgaria is the sixth on the list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
