<HEADLINE> Lesotho FM Defends SADC Military Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Foreign
Minister Tom Thabane Tuesday morning defended his government's
request for South African Development Community (SADC) military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The intervention follows a well judged situation by the four
SADC governments -- Mozambique, South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Botswana," South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Thabane
as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with SAPA, Thabane declined to say
when Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili had requested military
assistance from his SADC allies. He also declined to say whether
Mosisili and Lesotho cabinet ministers were still in the capital
of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Thabane said he was not in a position to comment on Tuesday's
intervention, and on the resulting gun battles and anarchy in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the intervention had been necessary as
Lesotho had experienced a complete breakdown in security on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The radio stationwas closed, the industrial areas were
closed, our Chinese investors were forced (by opposition youths)
to pack up and go home... There was general mayhem," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 800 soliders from South Africa, Botswana reportedly
entered Lesotho at 5:00 a.m. Tuesday morning to help restore
stability in the land-locked mountain kingdom at the request of
the embattled government of Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili.
</P>
