<HEADLINE> Reclamation Project Canceled To Save Mangroves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
recently canceled a 25-million-yuan reclamation project because
local experts believe it posed a threat to the growth of mangrove
forests in the coastal city of Longhai.
</P>
<P>
The project, initiated by the city government last year as a
key measure to enlarge its cultivated area, aimed to reclaim 460
hectares of marshland along the coast.
</P>
<P>
However, this area included 33 hectares of mangrove trees under
government protection, so experts from the provincial
environmental protection and forest departments called for an
immediate halt to the project in accordance with related laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The city government then reconsidered the reclamation plan and
decided to abandon it.
</P>
<P>
Mangroves usually grow in swampy area in the torrid and
subtropical zones, and they are able to protect and reinforce
river dikes with their exuberant roots.
</P>
<P>
The total area of mangrove forests in China has shrunk to
15,000 hectares from 50,000 in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Fujian, the northernmost mangrove habitat, put 200 hectares of
mangrove forests in Longhai under provincial protection in
1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adjusts Water Conservation Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Jiayu County, one of the most
seriously hit flood areas in China, is intensifying efforts to
change its water conservation strategy to deal with the water
situation.
</P>
<P>
According to a resettlement plan, evacuated farmers will no
longer return to towns that have been flooded, but will instead be
relocated elsewhere and the flooded places will become water
diversion areas when the floodwaters recede.
</P>
<P>
The county government plans to help rebuild homes in new places
for the farmers in three years to help them avoid moving around
whenever there is flood trouble as part of a nationwide campaign
to remove obstacles along major rivers and lakes that are
vulnerable to seasonal flooding. China had the devastating floods this
year, the worst since 1954.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists attribute the flooding partly to the
worsening struggle between local people and water over land along
major rivers and lakes. The total area of the eight big lakes
along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River, for
example, has been reduced by a third since the 1950s, something
that has greatly harmed their water control ability.
</P>
<P>
Hubei used to be known as the province of a thousand lakes, but
it now has only 309 lakes. To make matters worse, its growing
population has put pressure on land use. As a result, a large
amount of shoreland has become farmland, and rivers have been
narrowed.
</P>
<P>
The proposed Yangtze River economic belt will not fully develop
before human beings give way to water, water conservation,
specialists argue.
</P>
<P>
The lessons drawn from this year's record floods have shown how
to exist peacefully with rivers, and flood-damaged provinces like
Hunan, Hubei, and Jiangxi are all making an effort to leave more
room for water diversion areas while rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance recently issued 100 billion yuan in
treasury bonds, a large part of which will be used for major
rivers and lakes, with 30 billion yuan going to the Yangtze River
Valley, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
