<HEADLINE> Fishing Seminar in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) -- An international seminar on
the utilization of by-catch or incidental fish-harvesting -- those
non-targeted species caught in the process of fishing for other
species -- opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 experts from 24 countries and regions are
attendeding the three-day seminar as part of a ten-day session of
the Asia Pacific Fishery Commission (APFIC).
</P>
<P>
Though China has rapidly developed its fishing industry during
the past decade, the country still faces backward methods, said
an official of the Fishery Bureau of the Chinese Ministry of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this seminar has offered an opportunity for
China's experts to cooperate with their overseas counterparts on
the utilization of incidental fish-harvesting.
</P>
<P>
Yang Lin, an expert with the Chinese Academy of Fishery
Sciences, noted that China has been attempting to make full use of
these kinds of catch, but profits have been low.
</P>
<P>
The APFIC, an affiliate of the Food and Agriculture
Organization, now has 20 member countries including China. More
than 100 experts and officials from 39 countries and regions will
participate in the current Beijing session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
