<HEADLINE> Tianjin Strengthens Marine Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest port
city in north China, has spent more than 30 million yuan (about 3.7
million U.S. dollars) to install coal-washing facilities in the port
area to reduce coal dust pollution.
</P>
<P>
The city took this step in line with the city government's
regulations on protecting the marine environment. With 153
kilometers of coastline, Tianjin has jurisdiction over more than
3,000-square kilometers of marine area, and 370 square kilometers
of beach.
</P>
<P>
Marine oil fields are also being explored in the city's
offshore areas. The city government has worked out regulations
prohibiting oil-exploration corporations from polluting the
environment. All the residue and waste from oil drilling must be
recycled and treated, and all abandoned oil wells must be sealed
airtight.
</P>
<P>
No polluting enterprises are allowed to operate in the coastal
regions' nature reserves, scenic spots, and tourist areas, and
control measures have been taken in the agricultural sector to
reduce the use of chemical fertilizers and pesticides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
