<HEADLINE> Gold, Silver Prices Fall on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Gold and silver futures
fell sharply Monday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, following
a remarkable increase over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Gold for December delivery fell by 2.60 U.S. dollars to 291.60
dollars an ounce, while December silver fell by 12 cents to 4.855
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts noted the sharp decline of gold and silver
futures followed a remarkable jump of the precious metals to their
highest levels in nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
One of the main causes behind the ups and downs, they said, was
the prevailing concern that President Bill Clinton's videotaped
testimony on his relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky would highlight reasons to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
But with no immediate fresh surprises on the tapes, broadcast
Monday morning to the public, market participants began returning
to U.S. stocks and bonds, slashing demand for safe haven
investments such as precious metals.
</P>
<P>
Despite the losses, gold remains significantly above a 19-year
low of 273 U.S. dollars an ounce set in August, partly because of
a continued robust demand in India, the world's largest consumer
of gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
