<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Economic Growth May Slow Down: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The protracted flood in
Bangladesh this year will have an negative impact on the country's
economic growth, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) growth may slow down by at
least one percentage point, State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin
Alamgir was quoted Tuesday by The Daily Star newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
As the government's top economic planner, Alamgir was Monday
talking about the revision downward of the GDP growth target to 5
percent from the previously estimated 6 percent, but some
economists said the GDP growth could remain well below the level.
</P>
<P>
One economist said the rate might be as low as 4 percent,
considering the preliminary estimates of flood-caused losses at
3.4 billion U.S. dollars, about 10 percent of the country's GDP
and the huge damage to infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In the current Fifth Five-Year Plan (1998-2002), the
Bangladeshi government projected the GDP growth at an average
annual compound rate of 7 percent, with an estimated 6 percent for
the first year and 8.3 percent for the terminal year.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged flooding, which experts termed as the worst
Bangladesh has faced in this century and which lasted more than
two months before it began to recede last week, stopped most
economic activities in as many as 52 out of the country's 64
districts.
</P>
<P>
The government however remains optimistic about reaching the
five-point mark, hoping to cash in on largely-unaffected service
sectors and a likely bumper output of boro, unseasonal and
irrigated rice, in areas not hit by the floods, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the state minister, the nation's GDP is dominated
by the service sector which contributes more than 48 percent,
followed by agriculture 29 percent and industry 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Massive programs have been planned to rehabilitate agriculture
to minimize the flood damage. In unaffected areas, "we will have a
bumper boro and potato harvest," he said.
</P>
<P>
The service sector more or less remains unaffected and the
country's exports have escaped the onslaught of the deluge to a
large extent, according to the state minister, who is busy
estimating damage to the economy as croplands and homes of
millions have begun to emerge from under the flood water.
</P>
<P>
Economists said rehabilitation of agriculture would be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
Omar Haider Chowdhury, research director at Bangladesh
Institute of Development Studies (BIDS), said a bumper boro
harvest would not help much. "It would still be too far to reach
normal national rice production," he said. BIDS researcher Quazi
Shahabuddin agreed, saying rehabilitation of agriculture would be
difficult because "one cannot simply go for cultivation if it is
not a season for a crop."
</P>
<P>
Achieving a 4-percent growth in GDP would be a challenge to the
government. "If the economy grows at that rate this year, it will
be good news for the nation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Moyeen Khan, former state minister for planning, also
ruled out the chances of hitting the 5-percent target. "If
agriculture goes down, so does the GDP," he argued, referring to
the farming sector's dominance in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Economics Professor Wahiduddin Mahmud of Dhaka University
warned against "excessive monetary expansion and inflation" in the
wake of the government's special efforts to increase credit
facilities to the farmers.
</P>
<P>
It would not be a problem, if "increased credit meets the
genuine short-term needs for working capital," he said. "But if
funds are misused and credit discipline is jeopardized, not only
scarce resources will be wasted but also macroeconomic
stabilization will be put at great risk."
</P>
<P>
But the crisis also offers some opportunity for the government
when it comes to shedding unnecessary, politically-driven
projects, the professor pointed out. "The exercise of revising the
Annual Development Program also gives an opportunity for getting
rid of low-priority politically-mandated projects, which have
proliferated in recent years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned against "leakage of funds in public works" and
"compromising quality" when the government would be hurrying to
spend as much as possible to spur economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
