<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Good Signs in Bosnian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that some good results will come out of elections held this
month in Bosnia despite that a hardline nationalist will defeat
pro-West Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we would have far preferred Mrs. Plavsic to be
re-elected, you know that. But in the parliament it looks like the
moderates are doing reasonably all right, so we may be able to
make progress," said a defense official, who declined to be named.
</P>
<P>
"If you ask me if I think Bosnia's on a reasonable trend
line... I would expect the answer's yes," he told a briefing about
Defense Secretary William Cohen's trip to Europe later this week.
</P>
<P>
The official said the facts that the elections took place,
appeared to be fair and involved little violence were all good
signs.
</P>
<P>
"Our fundamental preference is to recreate a civil society in
Bosnia... and these are the third set of elections. That's not too
bad in terms of going forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think we're still on a trend line. I don't want to not
say there's a lot to be done, because there is a lot to be done,
but it's a set of elections, and we'll work with it."
</P>
<P>
Ballots cast in the September 12 and 13 elections are still
being counted, and the outcome is not expected to be announced
until the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had said before the election that it supported
Plavsic. But the Serb Radical Party's Nikola Poplasen is expected
to win the presidency of the autonomous Serb Republic in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Cohen's trip to Europe includes a meeting of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) in Portugal and visits to Macedonia and
Bosnia. 
</P>
