<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FloJo Was One of a Kind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Florence Griffith Joyner
only needed to beat the world records once, but the women's dash
events had died before she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
She was one of a special kind. No one could close to her
100-meter world record of 10.49 seconds. That is a record belongs
to the space world, no living female now and future could shatter
it.
</P>
<P>
Besides the fastest women's sprinter in history, she also
established the standards for fashion in track and field.
</P>
<P>
No one could match her speed 10 years ago, the 100m and 200m
world records stand still. And no one has duplicated the flair
she displayed -- her flamboyant, colorful, one-legged outfits,
her elaborate, well-polished, 6-inch fingernails.
</P>
<P>
Sprinter-hurdler Gail Devers and 400-meter hurdler Sandra
Farmer Patrick have tried to emulate the glamour of Griffith
Joyner, who died Monday of a heart-related problem at 38.
</P>
<P>
Devers, two-time Olympic 100 meter winner in 1992 and 1996, is
well known for her extremely long fingernails, and Farmer Patrick
for her stylish attire, but neither star has received the acclaim
nor captured the imagination of the flashy, provocative "FloJo."
</P>
<P>
Farmer Patrick was very sad after learning Griffith Joyner's
death. "Florence was like a sister to me," she said, crying
uncontrollably. "We shared so much together. We shared lots of
childhood memories and career goals. We had similar values and
religious beliefs."
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner was the godmother of Farmer Patrick's
4-year-old daughter, Sierra.
</P>
<P>
"I chose her because of her strength and her courage," Farmer
Patrick said. "I loved her dearly."
</P>
<P>
Even though there were rumblings during the 1988 Olympics that
Griffith Joyner was using performance-enhancing drugs because she
appeard bulked up. But she passed all drug tests and remained
clean.
</P>
<P>
Griffith was co-chair of the Presidnet's Council on Physical
Fitness and Sports.
</P>
<P>
"She was very good with kids," said John Smith, one of the
premier sprint coaches in the world. "Whenever she came to see
me, she brought a FloJo doll for my daughter."
</P>
<P>
"We're going to miss her. She made a great contribution to
track and field, like Wilma Rudolph did before her and like
Marion Jones is doing now."
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner authored many children's books, featuring the
character Barry Bam Bam, she wrote poems; she was a beautician,
an artist, a model and a clothes designer, she performed in
movies and television; she did numerous commercial endorsements;
she made many speaking engagements, and she designed the uniforms
for the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
Craig Masback, executive director of USA Track and Field, said
FloJo's records "might last into the 21st century," but that
should not be the only thing for which she is remembered.
</P>
<P>
"She revolutionized the way athletes dress. Her flair and
everything else she did captured the imagination," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0256 </DOCNO>
