<HEADLINE> Three Party Summit Held in Siem Reap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A summit meeting of Cambodia's
rival political leaders opened here Tuesday under the auspices of
King Norodom Sihanouk, aimed at defusing current political deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The meeting began at 9:30 am Tuesday at the King's Siem Reap
Palace.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, vice-president of the ruling Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) and Prince Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy of opposition Funcinpec and
Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and
deposed First Prime Minister Ranariddh had a face-to-face meeting
in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
CPP Vice-president Hun Sen and Funcinpec President Prince Ranariddh
were co-premiers in the last government, which emerged from the 1993
UN poll. But the prince was ousted after faction fighting in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
It's uncertain whether any substantive coalition issues will be
discussed and resolved at the summit, or whether the talks will deal
mostly with trying to heal deep wounds and prepare for Thursday's
event.
</P>
<P>
Opposition party officials said Monday the summit's success depends
on the King, but indicated that election results and the travel ban
are two issues that must be addressed.
</P>
<P>
The SRP said Monday, its delegation plans to introduce a series of
substantive items to be agreed upon in order firstly to create the
conditions for meaningful dialogue at the summit itself, and secondly
to determine fundamental goals for a possible coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Opposition supporters took to the streets of Phnom Penh over the
last three weeks to protest the election results and to demand the
resignation of Second Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk stepped into defuse the crisis when weeks of protests
erupted into violence following a police interference that left at
least two dead on the streets and scores of others injured and
missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
