<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Backs Czech Bid for EU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Austria fully supports the
Czech Republic in its effort to join the European Union (EU),
Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with the visiting Czech Prime Minister Milos
Zeman, Klima said the Sudeten problem should not stand in the way
of the Czech bid for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Sudeten, a region in the northwestern part of the Czech
Republic, was captured by the German army during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Even though most of the population are Germans, Sudeten was
returned to the Czech Republic after the war. However, the Czech
government started to drive Sudeten Germans out of the area,
triggering quarrels between Prague, Bonn and Vienna.
</P>
<P>
Both Klima and Zeman agreed to set up a committee to
investigate historical problems between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
At present, some Austrians have established -- as a
precondition for the Czech Republic to join the EU -- that Prague
should compensate the exiled Sudeten Germans.
</P>
<P>
Zeman said at a press conference that politics had to look
forward rather than backward, adding that the Sudeten problem
should be separated from its bid for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
"History belongs to historians," Zeman noted, saying that the
Czech Republic and Germany had signed a reconciliation statement
last year and the Sudeten problem was no longer regarded as a
major issue.
</P>
<P>
Zeman arrived in Vienna for a brief visit. He also met Austrian
President Thomas Klestil and President of the National Council
Heinz Fischer.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Central European countries will gather in Vienna on
October 12 to discuss EU expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
