<HEADLINE> Italian GDP Grows 1.8 Percent in First Half of 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy's gross domestic product
(GDP) grew 0.4 percent in the second quarter of 1998, bringing the
annual increase to 1.15 percent, the National Statistics Institute
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
For the entire first half of this year, GDP showed a growth of
1.8 percent, compared with a gain of 0.6 percent in the same
period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The institute said that Italy's economic growth was in line
with that of other major industrialized countries. France reported
a second-quarter growth of 0.7 percent, Britain 0.5 percent, the
U.S. 0.4 percent and Germany 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports of Italian commodities and services went up by 2.5
percent on a quarterly basis and household consumption 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Italian economy was expected to grow by 2.5 percent this
year, but the forecast was scaled back to two percent later. To
hit that target, the economy will have to climb 2.2 percent in the
remaining two quarters, the institute said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
