<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promises Closer Cooperation with IAEA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- China, as a nuclear weapon
state, advocated the complete prohibition and destruction of
nuclear weapons, and will continue its close cooperation with the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Zhang Huazhu, head of
the Chinese delegation, told the 42nd Session of the IAEA General
Conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
China had always supported the indefinite extension of the
Treaty on Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) and signed
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), Zhang said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen nuclear export controls, China joined the Zangger
Committee in October 1997 and formally promulgated the Regulation
of Nuclear Export Control of the People's Republic of China last
year, and the Regulation of Nuclear Dual-Use Items Export Control
of the People's Republic of China this year.
</P>
<P>
"The promulgation and implementation of these two regulations
have put nuclear exports and nuclear-related dual use items
exports on a legally controlled track, which has positive
significance for promoting nuclear cooperation and nuclear trade
between China and other countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
To meet demand for electricity in its economic development,
China had successfully constructed two nuclear power plants in the
1990s with a total installed capacity of 2,100 MW, which have been
operating smoothly, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
During the Ninth Five Year Plan, China planned to build another
four big nuclear power plants, with a total of eight units and the
total installed capacity of 6,600 megawatts, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that preventing the proliferation of nuclear
weapons was still a pressingly important task. "The nuclear tests
conducted in May by India, which went against the trend, and then
by Pakistan, shocked the international community and met universal
opposition.
</P>
<P>
"The acts of India and Pakistan are a hard blow on the
international effort to prevent the proliferation of nuclear
weapons and constitute a big challenge to the global nuclear
non-proliferation regime of which the NPT is the cornerstone," the
Chinese official stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also urged India and Pakistan to fully implement
U.N. Security Council Resolution number 1172, abandon their
nuclear weapon development programs and accede to the CTBT and NPT
immediately and unconditionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
