<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Talks Stalled Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The NBA owners and
players failed to set up a bargaining session because both sides
couldn't agree on the basic rules.
</P>
<P>
Deputy commissioner Russ Granik and players union president
Billy Hunter both acknowledged Monday that talks aimed at closing
the lockout could have resumed almost a week and a half ago,
though they differed on why such a get-together never took place.
</P>
<P>
Since the lockout beginning on July 1, both sides only held
one formal bargaining session, and the league is to begin
canceling exhibition games later this week.
</P>
<P>
"We invited players to come back to the table, and they
declined," Granik said. "They said as long as we would be talking
about a hard cap or some system that set a defined percentage of
revenues to go toward player salaries, they didn't see any point
of meeting."
</P>
<P>
Hunter said he had proposed to have a meeting with four
representatives from each side. But he refused to do so when
commissioner David Stern insisted that the owners' labor
committee should send eight members to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"I just don't think it's progressive or beneficial when there
are 40 people in the room," said Hunter, who nonetheless tried to
call Granik on Monday afternoon to discuss moving the process f
orward.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are still waiting for a decision from arbitrator
John Feerick, who will rule on the players' grievance contending
that some 220 players with 800 million worth of guaranteed
contracts should be paid during the lockout. But Feerick's
ruling is not expected until early October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
