<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Reports Less Private Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Private capitals entering
Latin American countries and the Caribbean dropped drastically
from 26.2 billion U.S. dollars in the 1996 fiscal year to 13.6
billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) reported on Monday that
capital fluctuations were caused by the closure of foreign banks
in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the reform and restructuring of the Latin American
banking system -- relevant to private capital -- were also
affected by Southeast Asia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The effects of Asia's financial debt crisis in Latin America
were more evident in September 1997. Argentina, Panama and
Venezuela bought global 30-year bonds for a total of 7 billion
U.S. dollars," IMF reported. The deepening of the Asian crisis
only increased the debt of the Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 1997 fiscal year, the debt of Latin America
and the Caribbean grew to 4.636 billion dollars, compared with
4.263 billions dollars during the previous fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0268 </DOCNO>
