<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Has 30 percent of State Budget Untouched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 22 (Xinhua) -- With less than two weeks left
in the fiscal year, nearly 30 percent of the Thai government's
budget remains unspent, the Bangkok Post newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the Finance Ministry is working to speed up
disbursements, at least half of the remaining money is unlikely to
be spent before this fiscal year ends on September 30, the
newspaper said, quoting Deputy Finance Minister Pichet
Phanvichartkul.
</P>
<P>
As of last Thursday, 580 billion baht (14.5 billion U.S.
dollars) had been disbursed from the 830-billion-baht (20.7
billion-dollar) budget for fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministry expects to disburse 134 billion baht (3.4 billion
dollars) by the end of the month, bringing total disbursements to
714 billion baht (17.9 billion dollars) or 86 percent of the total
budget.
</P>
<P>
Delays in budget disbursements and last-minute spending sprees
are nothing new, said the newspaper. But this year officials blame
the delays on the need to adhere to strict conditions set earlier
by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), it said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF subsequently agreed to relax constraints, allowing the
government to run a deficit.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal 1998 budget of 830 billion baht contained a
provision for a deficit of up to 117 billion baht (2.9 billion
dollars) or 2.4 percent of gross domestic product (GDP). State
enterprises were allowed to run a maximum deficit of no more than
0.6 percent of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
