<HEADLINE> 42nd IAEA Conference Held in Vienna </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The nuclear tests in India and
Pakistan look set to top the agenda at the 42nd session of the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) General Conference which
began in Vienna on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference will also discuss schedules and budgets
for 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear plans of Iraq and the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea, and the nuclear tests in India and Pakistan will also
among the discussions of delegates.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory message to the conference, U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan said a common goal for the world was to set up
efficient global and regional systems of nuclear security with no
more nuclear tests or weapons.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged all countries to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, a supplement to the non-proliferation treaty.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a nuclear disarmament to be carried out as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Every country with nuclear devices should ensure nuclear
safety, he added. The international community should help the
IAEA to crack down on smuggling of nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 representatives from about 100 countries are
attending the conference, including senior officials from the
United States, Russia and China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
