<HEADLINE> Czech Foreign Trade Deficit Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The Czech foreign trade
deficit fell 46.7 percent in the first eight months of this year
as a result of growth in imports and exports, the country's
statistics bureau said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Imports for the first eight months grew 13.3 percent to reach
613 billion korunas (19.9 billion U.S. dollars) while exports
increased 27.5 percent to 567.09 billion korunas (18.3 billion
U.S. dollars), the statistics bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the foreign trade deficit fell from 98.31 billion
korunas (3.17 billion U.S. dollars) to 45.91 billion korunas (1.48
billion U.S. dollars) in the first eight months, according to the
bureau.
</P>
<P>
Czech financial experts considered the economic situation this
year as the best since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade deficit was dangerously high in the past four
years as it hit 160 billion korunas (5.1 billion U.S. dollars) and
140 billion korunas (4.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Czech government has taken many steps to encourage exports
and limit imports in order to reduce the foreign trade deficit
which is a serious problem for the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
