<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Seeks Emergency Funds for Safe Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration
said Monday it wants 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in emergency funds
to rebuild the embassies destroyed by bombs last month and to beef
up security at U.S. facilities around the world.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official told a briefing that the U.S. administration
would send its request to the Congress later this week.
</P>
<P>
Of the funding request, about 1.4 billion dollars would be used
to rebuild the U.S. embassies in Kenya and in Tanzania, which were
destroyed by bombs on August 7, and to beef up security at
U.S. facilities worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Much of the remaining money would provide aid to Kenya and
Tanzania to help the families of those killed in the bombings and
help pay the medical expenses of those injured.
</P>
<P>
Officials who briefed reporters on the emergency package said
the administration would likely seek more such funding next year.
