<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Team Confirms Rapes During May Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Joint
Fact-Finding Team investigating the May riots in the country
asserted on Monday that despite some officials' denials, sexual
assaults and rapes did take place in the unrest in Jakarta and
other cities.
</P>
<P>
"We confirmed to the government that sexual assaults including
rapes occurred during the May riots," team chairman Marzuki
Darusman was quoted by the newspaper The Jakarta Post Tuesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki told this to reporters after meeting Minister of
Defense and Security/Armed Forces Commander Gen. Wiranto, Minister
of Justice Muladi and State Minister of Women's Affairs Tutty
Alawiyah at the Ministry of Justice on Monday.
</P>
<P>
When asked to elaborate on the basis of the team's statement,
Marzuki said the 19-member team had access to sources of
information about the sexual assaults during the riots.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that a number of team members had met with
victims of the sexual assaults and rapes.
</P>
<P>
"We will convey the complete report (on sexual assaults and
rapes during the riots) when we announce our final report in
October. The important thing is we want to assure that these
things have happened and this is accepted by the government," he
said.
</P>
<P>
From May 13 to 15, the country saw the worst looting and
rioting in decades in Jakarta, Medan and Solo, killing more than
1,200 people and damaging thousands of buildings and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The government established the Joint Fact-Finding Team on July
23 which includes representatives from the Armed Forces,
government agencies, the National Commission on Human Rights and
non-governmental organizations to investigate reports that the
riots were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Activists, including those in the Volunteers for Humanity led
by Catholic priest Sandyawan Sumardi, have said 168 women and
children were raped or sexually assaulted during the riots, 20 of
whom died or committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
Sandyawan is one of the Joint Fact-Finding Team members.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the team met the ministers on Monday to
deliver an interim report on its investigation into the May riots.
The team is expected to complete its task by October 23.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto told reporters after a two-hour meeting with the team
that they had collected "a lot of facts as well as information"
relating to the rapes alleged to have occurred during the riots.
</P>
<P>
"The team has gathered a lot of facts and information and
shared them with us (the government). We will use them to
complement the inputs the government has previously received on
the incidents," Wiranto added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Preparing Yarlung Zangbo River Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region
is preparing an expedition along the Yarlung Zangbo River to make
the deepest valley in the world more available to tourists.
</P>
<P>
Tang Zhengqi, director of the Tourism Administrative Bureau of
Tibet, told the First Southwest China Tourism Promotion Fair in
Guiyang, the capital of Guizhou Province, recently that visitors
can see a variety of ecosystems and vegetations similar to that of
areas ranging from the equator to the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
The 496-km-long Yarlung Zangbo is in the southeastern part of
Tibet and is regarded as the highest river in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Yarlung Zangbo Valley, which is more than 5,000 meters
deep, is also the longest and deepest on earth.
</P>
<P>
An arrangement will be made to fly visitors to Lhasa, the
capital of Tibet, then to take them more than 500 km by bus to
Bomi County, and then to provide an expedition along the valley on
foot.
</P>
<P>
The program is scheduled to start in 2000 and if possible, an
airport will be open in Nyingchi especially for the expedition,
Tang says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
