<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Allow Private Firms to Import Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
will allow private companies to import good-quality rice and sell
it directly to consumers to help boost supply on the domestic
market, a minister was quoted by The Jakarta Post Tuesday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Private-sector imports would be restricted to first- and
second-grade rice while the State Logistics Agency (Bulog) would
continue to import lower grades, State Minister of Food Affairs
and Horticulture A.M. Saefuddin said in a hearing with House of
Representatives Commission III for agriculture and food affairs on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said private traders importing rice would be exempt from
import duties and value-added tax.
</P>
<P>
The market for first- and second-grade rice, which is mainly
consumed by the country's rich, was big enough to make the trade a
viable commercial proposition.
</P>
<P>
"Imports of good quality rice will be limited to only 600,000
tons in this fiscal year because it is consumed by only 20 percent
of the total population," Saefuddin said.
</P>
<P>
Harvest failure has prompted the government to commit itself to
importing 4.1 million tons of rice in this fiscal year beginning
April.
</P>
<P>
Contracts have been signed for the import of 2.4 million tons
of rice, some of which has already been delivered. Of the
remaining 1.7 million tons, Bulog last week procured 526,000 tons
through a competitive bidding process and contracts to import a
further 674,000 tons will shortly be put out to tender. The
remainder is expected to be good-quality rice imported by private
companies.
</P>
<P>
Saefuddin told the House that half of the country has been hit
by food shortages.
</P>
<P>
He said 150 of the country's 308 regencies were facing a food
shortfall, adding that shortages in 53 of these regencies were
severe.
</P>
<P>
"Shortfalls exist in 25 of Indonesia's 27 provinces. Only
Jakarta and Bali are not facing a shortfall. In Jakarta, only the
urban poor in slum areas are vulnerable to food shortages," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government is taking several steps to combat the problem,
including increasing rice imports, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
