<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Helps Tibetans Regain Their Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 22 (Xinhua) -- A 40-year-old Tibetan woman who
suffered from cataract-related blindness for many years and who
had not seen her 15-year-old son, regained her sight when doctors
from Beijing performed eye surgery on her three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The woman, Cangjue, burst into tears, and said, "I thought I
would see nothing for the rest of my life," as she thanked the
doctors.
</P>
<P>
She is one of 980 cataract patients who have regained their
sight since a medical team started providing surgery for free in
the Tibet Autonomous Region since August in a program sponsored by
"Sight First China Action", whose intention is to help 1.75
million Chinese cataract sufferers regain their sight before the
year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The program was started by the Ministry of Health, the Chinese
Disabled Persons' Federation, and Lions Clubs International in
August of last year.
</P>
<P>
The people of Tibet run a much higher risk of cataracts because
of excessive exposure to ultraviolet rays. The incidence of
cataracts is twice as high as in other parts of China, and they
generally appear 10 to 15 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
People can not do farm or even household work, making their
lives much harder. Cangjue thought that she would have to make her
son quit school and help the family with their cattle as a result.
</P>
<P>
"We're very concerned about the serious situation in Tibet,"
says Wang Chengjin, vice chairman of the executive council of the
disabled persons' organization. He explains that the medical team
consists of some 20 leading ophthalmologists from hospitals in the
cities of Beijing, Xi'an, Chongqing and Lhasa. They traveled about
4,600 kilometers to remote towns and counties in spite of mountain
sickness, and bad weather, and poor road conditions.
</P>
<P>
"It's an opportunity both for local patients and us. I've never
been so excited and happy as when Cangjue could see again," says
Doctor Li Meiju, of Beijing's General Hospital of the Air Force,
who removed Cangjue's cataract and added the artificial lens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Courts Recover State Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 22 (Xinhua) - Chinese courts handled
258,000 criminal cases and convicted 265,000 defendants during the
first seven months this year, according Xiao Yang, president of
the Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Xiao told participants in a recent conference that the
nation's courts issued judgments leading to the recovery of four
billion yuan (about 500 million U.S. dollars) in assets belonging
to the State and collectives.
</P>
<P>
Chinese courts have focused on prosecuting cases involving
heinous crimes, drug traffickers, publishers of illegal and
obscene materials, smugglers and corrupt public officials.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the January-July period show that Chinese courts
handled 258,000 criminal cases of the first instance, up 7.39
percent on the previous year's period. The courts handed down
judgments in 222,000 cases, down 3.97 percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The courts convicted 123,000 felons involved in disrupting
social order and 15,000 individuals charged with economic crimes,
including 217 high-ranking county and 21 prefectural
(departmental) officials.
</P>
<P>
Xiao noted the courts have witnessed a sharp increase in
financial disputes.
</P>
<P>
"State-owned commercial banks have recorded a relatively high
ratio of bad loans, various non-financial institutions have
engaged in illegal financial transactions, irregularities have
surfaced in the nation's stock and futures markets, and there has
been a upsurge in the number of fraud cases," according to Xiao.
</P>
<P>
He said courts issued judgments in 223,000 financial cases
during the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Courts have accelerated efforts to handle the increasing number
of cases related to the reform of state-owned enterprises,
land-use contracts in rural areas and both real estate and labor
disputes. The efforts of the courts center on safeguarding
economic development and social stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
