<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   U.S. Still Has Land to Return to Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government still
has under its jurisdiction 23,215 hectares of land to be returned
to Panama, Panama's Interoceanic Regional Authority (IRA) said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter Treaty, signed by the two countries
in 1977, the land will be transferred gradually by December 31,
1999, the IRA said.
</P>
<P>
Panama plans to develop industrial, tourist, commercial and
maritime projects at the U.S. military bases of Fort Kobbe,
Cocoli, Corozal, Fort Sherman, Fort Clayton, Howard and Rodman,
where there are still 4,500 U.S. personnel.
</P>
<P>
The transfer is carried out under the guidelines set by
Panamanian President Ernesto Perez Balladares in the law that
contains the General Use, Conservation and Development Plan of the
Canal area and for the development of the returned land.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government is expected to invest 103 million
U.S. dollars to achieve the proposed goals.
</P>
<P>
According to the IRA's plans, there will be reforestation
projects as well as installation of public institutions and
non-government organizations over 12,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has returned a total of 70,000 hectares to Panama
since 1979, when the New Canal Treaty was put into effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
