<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Wedding Culture Faces Challenge from West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Young Asians shouldn't lose
their traditional wedding culture to the irresistible trend toward
a Western living style, a Japanese wedding expert said recently at
the 4th Asian Wedding Culture Symposium held in the northeast
China coastal city of Dalian.
</P>
<P>
Yumi Katsura, head of the Japan Wedding Culture Association,
said Japanese wedding culture is being Westernized these days, and
the same thing is happening in the Republic of Korea (ROK) and
China.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that more than half of Japanese newlyweds
hold their wedding ceremonies in churches and wear Western-style
wedding dress. Another 30 percent wear both Western dress and
Japanese traditional dress.
</P>
<P>
Yumi Katsura said that Asian tradition should coexist with
Western culture, not be eroded by it.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, different nationalities have their own traditional
wedding culture with elaborate rites and colorful costumes.
</P>
<P>
An the symposium, experts and wedding dress designers from
Japan, India, the ROK and other Asian countries exchanged views on
the promotion and protection of traditional Asian wedding
culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
