<HEADLINE> Avon Shifts from Direct Sales to Retailing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Former direct-sales giant
Guangzhou Avon Co. Ltd. has recently turned to retail and whole
selling in China with the approval of the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
As a joint venture between Avon of the United States and a
local company in Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong Province,
Guangzhou Avon became the first direct-sales company in China in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Since the State Council issued a ban on direct selling in China
in April, Guangzhou Avon has been busy adjusting its operations.
</P>
<P>
After getting approval on September 9, Guangzhou Avon and its
68 subsidiaries in China will soon be doing retail and wholesale
business in shops.
</P>
<P>
The company recently invested 40 million U.S. dollars to build
a new factory in the city of Conghua in Guangdong Province. The
new facility is expected to become operational this November.
</P>
<P>
Avon is the world's largest direct-sales cosmetics dealer,
with annual sales of 5.1 billion U.S. dollars. By 1997,
the company had invested 70 million U.S. dollars in China, and
sales that year hit 75 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou Avon has paid taxes of 55 million U.S. dollars in
China thus far.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Suffers More From UV-B Radiation: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- "The amount of
ultraviolet-B (UV-B) reaching the earth's surface of New Zealand
is higher than northern hemisphere countries that are at an
equivalent latitude," a New Zealand expert said.
</P>
<P>
Brian Jordan, director of the Monogastric Research Center of
the Massey University, said the reason for higher level of UV-B
radiation in New Zealand is that the country has clear skies with
no pollution to act as a "filter," the local newspaper The
Dominion Tuesday reported.
</P>
<P>
Because of the higher level of UV-B radiation, New Zealand has
already become "one of the highest incidences of skin cancer in
the world," said Jordan, who has just returned from a U.N. meeting
in Hawaii on the environmental effects of ozone depletion and UV-B
radiation.
</P>
<P>
He said the impact of pouring chemical by-products into the
atmosphere would continue to deplete ozone for 50 years despite
international cleanup measures.
</P>
<P>
Jordan called on New Zealanders to maintain "vigilance of the
long-term possibility of increasing levels of UV-B radiation."
</P>
<P>
"High levels of UV-B are damaging but our behavior can reduce
the risk," he said. "For humans, keeping out of the midday sun and
covering up are two simple but effective protective measures."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cow Bones May Be Used in Humans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 22 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in Hamilton in

New Zealand's North Island have made a breakthrough in molding
human
joint implants out of cow bones, the New Zealand Press Association

(NZPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said the achievement of the Waikato University scientists
and
the Meat Industry Research Institute of New Zealand is expected to

benefit cancer patients and crash victims.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have found a way to turn cow thigh bones from
the
abattoir into a dry, softer substance that doctors can cut for use

in non-load-bearing human joints. Those who will benefit include
bone cancer patients, accident victims with bone-crush injuries,
people with birth deformities, arthritis patients and people
wanting
cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
The NZPA said the government-funded research has been conducted

for two years and the purified bone they have developed is called
calcium phosphate. Overseas doctors already use it in a synthetic
form, but it is costly to import. The Hamilton researchers found a

much cheaper way to make it naturally.
</P>
<P>
The process involves cutting the top off the yellow bone,
pressure-cooking it to kill bugs and remove fat and blood, soaking
it
in solvents to remove the last traces of fat, bleaching it and
agitating it to remove collagen.
</P>
<P>
The next step is animal and human trials, the NZPA said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0305 </DOCNO>
