<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, September 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Eight countries on Monday evening concluded a
meeting on Afghanistan, with a joint call for an immediate
ceasefire and negotiations aimed at peaceful solution to the
conflicts in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"With a view toward ending conflict inside Afghanistan, and
ending further bloodshed, the Taliban and other parties should
declare an immediate ceasefire and undertake negotiations aimed at
achieving a political settlement culminating in the establishment
of a broad-based, multi-ethnic, representative government," a news
release said at the end of the meeting. (UN-meeting Afghanistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni Monday afternoon
accepted the presentation of credentials of four ambassadors newly
accredited to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said that the four
envoys are from Belgium, Denmark, India and Japan.
(Uganda-Foreign Envoys)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian permanent envoy to the Arab League
Mohammed Sobeih said on Monday that the U.S. is preparing for a
tripartite summit on the Mideast peace process among leaders of
the U.S., Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, among U.S. President Bill Clinton, PNA President
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on the
fringe of the 53rd U.N. General Assembly session, will be part of
the U.S. efforts, under the U.N. sponsorship, to push forward the
Israeli-Palestinian preace process, Sobeih told Egypt's Middle
East News Agency (MENA). (Palestine-US-Tripartite Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday
called for global action in an anti-terrorism campaign because
individual action by U.N. member states cannot provide a solution.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism is a global menace, which clearly calls for global
action," he said. "Individual actions by member states, whether
aimed at state of non-state actor, cannot in themselves provide a
solution. We must meet this threat together." (UN-Annan's
Speech-Terrorism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The 53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly
Monday began a two-week general debate, in which speakers from 181
countries are expected to voice their views of a wide range of
matters of international concern.
</P>
<P>
The speakers include 26 heads of state, 19 prime ministers, 12
deputy prime ministers and foreign ministers, and 109 foreign
ministers, U.N. officials said. (UN-General Assembly) 
</P>
