<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Johnson Fails in Lifting Lifetime Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian sprinter Ben Johnson
failed on Monday in its latest attempts to overturn the lifetime
ban when an appeal court quickly dismissed his appeal.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that a lower court did the right thing last
summer when it refused to lift Johnson's ban from track and
field, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The sprinter looked stunned when given the verdict. Earlier,
he said that he would appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada if
the appeal court did't rule in his favor.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old Canadian was still hoping to return to the
track and field 10 years after his Seoul Olympic gold was
stripped after testing positive for a banned steroid.
</P>
<P>
At that time, he was handed a two-year suspension from
competing.
</P>
<P>
He returned to sprinting in 1991, and took part in a semifinal
of the 100 meters event at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
But when he tested positive for the second time at a track
meet in Montreal in 1993, the International Amateur Athletics
Federation imposed a lifetime ban on him.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Johnson asked the general division of Ontario Court
to lift the ban from competition. His request was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
If Canadian courts had ruled that his ban should be lifted,
the federation might have allowed Johnson to compete again, the
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission, IOC Start Direct Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee president on Monday visited the European Commission to
start a dialogue between the world governing body of sports and
the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue went underway as Juan Antonio Samaranch and
European Sports Commissioner Marcelino Oreja discussed the model
of European sports, the relations between sports and television
industry and the role sports plays in the framework of politics
and society.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, is drafting a legal text devoted not only to the
subject of competition and broadcasting rights but also to public
health and youth protection policy.
</P>
<P>
The 20-member commission is to debate a statement regarding
the drafting of the legal text.
</P>
<P>
The commission is concerned about the doping problem in sports
and the IOC invited Oreja to attend the global anti-doping
conference slated for next February in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The commission has already approved the ban on tobacco
sponsorship for sports and arts events in the European Union and
the ban is expected to enter into full force in 2006 at the
latest.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner briefed Samaranch on his intention to propose
to the commission the designation of the year 2004 as the
European Year of Sports due to the fact the 2004 Summer Olympic
Games will be held in Greece.
</P>
<P>
Present at the dialogue were also representatives from
international sports federations and television broadcasters.
</P>
</TEXT>
