<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chelsea Stuns Blackburn in English Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Two late goals from Norwegian
substitute Tore Andre Flo helped Chelsea beat Blackburn Rovers
4-3 after the two sides finished the English Premier league match
with 10 men.
</P>
<P>
A night of drama and two penalties at Ewood Park also saw
Blackburn's French defender Sebastian Perez grab his first goal
for the club and then get sent off in the 68th minute with
Chelsea's former Blackburn player Graeme Le Saux.
</P>
<P>
The lanky Flo was on the pitch for only around 14 minutes but
he had an immediate effect with the equaliser in the 82nd minute
and then a fine winner in the 86th with the assistance of fellow
substitute, Danish international Brian Laudrup.
</P>
<P>
European Cup Winners' Cup holders Chelsea had opened the
scoring in the 15th minute with a curling Gianfranco Zola
free-kick that flew over the wall and past the flailing Tim
Flowers. It was the Italian's second goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
Chris Sutton then equalised in the 22nd through the legs of Le
Saux and Blackburn should have gone in at the interval ahead
after Garry Flitcroft missed a good 45th-minute chance.
</P>
<P>
Chelsea forged ahead again after the break with a 51st-minute
penalty taken by French World Cup winner Franck Leboeuf after
Flowers was deemed to have brought down Zola.
</P>
<P>
Perez made up the gap in the 68th minute with a neat
close-range goal from a Flitcroft overhead kick but 10 minutes
later he and Le Saux went off after a touchline clash with the
Chelsea player lashing out and Perez falling to the ground.
</P>
<P>
Perez was also booked, controversially and for reasons that
were clearly unclear to his irate manager Roy Hodgson, and
trudged off having picked up a yellow card earlier.
</P>
<P>
A disappointed Hodgson later denounced several of the
referee's decisions, including the Chelsea penalty, and said that
Perez paid the price for having "had the misfortune to put his
nose in the way of someone else's elbow".
</P>
<P>
Sutton doubled his tally with a 79th-minute penalty after a
foul on Swedish international Martin Dahlin that looked to have c
linched the match but then Flo came on. The Norwegian was unlucky
not to have finished with a hat-trick.
</P>
<P>
The result lifted Chelsea to 11th place on eight points and
left Blackburn struggling in 18th on four. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
