<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Industry to Conduct Large-scale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, September 21 (Xinhua) -- In an unprecedented
effort, the U.S. retail industry will survey 82,000 retail vendors
in the country on their readiness for the year 2000 computer
problem.
</P>
<P>
The survey is under the auspices of the National Retail
Federation's Survival 2000 Project. The federation is scheduled to
send a joint letter Monday signed by 37 prominent retailers
including Sears, J.C. Penney and the Home Depot to vendors
spanning the entire retail supply chain to determine their ability
to deal with potential computer problems.
</P>
<P>
The letter notes that "the failure of an organization to become
Year 2000 compliant may seriously jeopardize or impair critical
business operations."
</P>
<P>
As there are less than 500 days left before the end of the
millennium, the federation said in a statement, an organized,
cross-industry survey is highly necessary and serve to build
awareness and to provide valuable information to participants.
</P>
<P>
The distribution of the letter demonstrates retailers' reliance
on merchandise vendors, malls, telecommunications providers and
numerous other companies for smooth operations. This landmark
joint effort marks the first time an industry has approached this
number of business partners.
</P>
<P>
The National Retail Federation (NRF) is the world's largest
retail trade association. Its members represent an industry that
encompasses more than 1.4 million U.S. retail establishments,
employs 20 million people and registered 1997 sales of over 2.5
trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In October, the federation will conduct a roundtable discussion
on the Y2K issue, NRF announced earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
