<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Countries Call for Peaceful Solution in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- Eight countries on
Monday evening concluded a meeting on Afghanistan, with a joint
call for an immediate ceasefire and negotiations aimed at peaceful
solution to the conflicts in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"With a view toward ending conflict inside Afghanistan, and
ending further bloodshed, the Taliban and other parties should
declare an immediate ceasefire and undertake negotiations aimed at
achieving a political settlement culminating in the establishment
of a broad-based, multi-ethnic, representative government," a news
release said at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, sponsored by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
was held on the sidelines of the current 53rd session of the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"All forces should immediately release non-combatants in
detention, including Iranians," the representatives from eight
countries, namely six of Afghanistan's neighbors plus Russia and
the United States. .
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban should expedite the return of the remains of the
three Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan, cooperate fully with an
international investigation into the killing of Iranian diplomats
and United Nations staff in Afghanistan, and bring the guilty
parties to justice," the meeting participants said.
</P>
<P>
"United Nations humanitarian assistance should be resumed as
soon as possible, with all factions providing safe and secure
conditions under internationally accepted norms," they stressed.
</P>
<P>
Present at the Monday meeting were Chinese Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan and his counterparts from Pakistan, Russia, the
United States and Uzebekistan. Iranian deputy foreign minister,
permanent representatives to the United Nations from Tajikistan
and Turkimenistan also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tension in the Afghan area resulted from both escalating
conflicts inside Afghanistan and the worsened situation in the
border areas between Iran and Afghanistan, the latter was due to
the killing of nine Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
