<HEADLINE> China: Afghan Issue Should be Solved by Afghan People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The question of
Afghanistan should be solved by the Afghan people and the Afghan
people have the ability to solve the problem of their own, China
stressed here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after attending a meeting on Afghanistan
which was initiated by the U.N. Secretary-General, Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan said as a neighboring country of
Afghanistan, China of course was following very closely the
developments in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that all factions in Afghanistan will
immediately achieve a ceasefire and the national reconciliation,
and China had consistently believed that the question of
Afghanistan should be solved by the Afghan people free from
external intervention," said Tang who is here to attend the
general debate of the 53rd session of the general Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"China has consistently opposed terrorism of any form and we
deeply deplore and regret the unfortunate killing of 9 Iranian
diplomats not long ago in Afghanistan which is entirely a serious
humanitarian crime and also a breach of international law. So the
Chinese Government strongly condemns such kind of act," Tang
continued.
</P>
<P>
"We are also following with great concern the recent
developments in the the border areas of Iran and Afghanistan.
China hopes that the parties concerned will keep calm and
exercise restraints and to settle their disputes through
dialogues and consultations in the interest of the peace and
stability in the region and in the interest of the appropriate
settlement of the Afghan issue," Tang stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980922.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Ease of Iran-Afghan Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The statement came as Annan was opening a meeting of eight
countries, namely representatives from six neighbors of
Afghanistan plus Russia and the United States to defuse tension
between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"A particular danger is posed by the increase in tension in the
border areas between Iran and Afghanistan. This threat, if allowed
to continue unattended, poses a very real danger to the peace and
stability of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Together with the endless sufferings of the Afghan people,
this is a source of deep concern for me and the international
community at large," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Afghanistan meeting, sponsored by the United Nations, clearly
demonstrates the concern of the international community over recent
development between Iran and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The tension in the border areas between Iran and Afghanistan
was triggered by the killing of nine Iranian diplomats in
Afghanistan. Declaring that it reserves the right to take any
action to revenge, Tehran has maintained a buildup of 200,000
troops in its border areas with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Afghanistan has gone from bad to worse in
recent weeks, as the Taliban movement intensified its offensives
in the northern part of the country," Annan said, "The fighting ...
has led to further destruction and loss of life in a country
that had already been devastated by 20 years of war."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "It is in the interest of all the States
represented here to end the conflict in Afghanistan and ensure
peace and stability in the region," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that today's meeting will send out message to those in
the region that the high-level delegations represented here this
afternoon are united in the conviction that the situation in
Afghanistan and the region should not be allowed to deteriorate
any further," he added.
</P>
<P>
"What is solely needed in Afghanistan is a representative and
inclusive government which truly reflects the interests of all
ethnic and religious groups in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The militia Taliban, which controls most of Afghanistan, was
not represented at the meeting, held on the sidelines of the U.N.
General Assembly session, as a majority of U.N. members refused to
recognize it as the solely legitimate representative of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Chineses Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and his counterparts
from Pakistan, Russia, the United States and Uzbekistan attended
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were deputy foreign minister of
Iran and permanent representatives to the United Nations from
Tajikistan and Turkmenistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
