<HEADLINE> U.N. Urged to Contribute to African Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
should reinforce the mechanism of conflict resolution in Africa,
said Burkina Faso President Blaise Compaore here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is because no external mechanism could achieve lasting
peace in the continent, he told the U.N. General Assembly on
behalf of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
On economic matters, he said Africa has spared no efforts to
establish an internal climate conducive to economic growth and
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
After years of stagnation, a new era of courageous reform in
the management of state affairs has emerged, he said, adding that
the goal is to set up the African Economic Community in the first
half of the next century.
</P>
<P>
Compaore said it was time to rethink the role of international
organizations in regulating the world economy, so that the
widening gap between rich and poor would not continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of the U.N. reform, Compaore said it
is unthinkable that an African representative is not seated on the
Security Council when Africa accounts for one third of the U.N.
members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
